{"title_page": "Central African oyan", "text_new": "{{About|the species of linsang|the genus of linsangs|Poiana (genus)}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Em - Poiana richardsonii 2.jpg\n| name = Central African oyan\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Poiana richardsonii'' |author=Gaubert, P. |author2=Do Linh San, E. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T41704A45219609 |date=2015 |access-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n| taxon = Poiana richardsonii<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000414 |heading=Species ''Poiana richardsonii''}}</ref>\n| authority = [[Thomas Richard Heywood Thomson|Thomson]], 1842\n| range_map = African Linsang area.png\n| range_map_caption = Central African oyan range\n}}\n\nThe '''Central African oyan''' (''Poiana richardsonii''), also called '''Central African linsang''', is a [[Poiana (genus)|linsang]] [[species]] native to [[Central Africa]].<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==Characteristics==\nThe Central African oyan's body is slender and long, with an elongated head and a pointed muzzle. Its fur is yellowish to reddish brown with darker spots on the back and flanks. Its throat and belly are lighter in colour and without spots. Its tail has 9 to 14 dark rings. Its body is {{convert|33-43|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, and the tail about the same length. Its legs are short, and the soles of its feet hairy. Females are slightly smaller than males.<ref name=VanRompaey2013>{{cite book |author=Van Rompaey, H. and Colyn, M. | year=2013 |chapter=''Poiana richardsonii'' Central African Linsang (Central African Oyan) |title=The Mammals of Africa. V. Carnivores, Pangolins, Equids and Rhinoceroses |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London |pages=253\u2212254 |editor=Kingdon, J. |editor2=Hoffmann, M. }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe Central African oyan is [[endemic]] to [[Cameroon]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Gabon]], the [[Central African Republic]], the [[Republic of the Congo]], and the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] east to the [[Albertine Rift]]. It lives in lowland and montane [[tropical rainforest]]s.<ref name=iucn/>\nIn Gabon, a [[camera-trap]] recorded an individual on the forest floor.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Bahaa-el-din, L., Henschel, P., Aba\u2019a, R., Abernethy, K., Bohm, T., Bout, N., Coad, L., Head, J., Inoue, E., Lahm, S., Lee, M. E., Maisels, F., Rabanal, L., Starkey, M., Taylor, G., Vanthomme, A., Nakashima, Y. and Hunter, L. |year= 2013 |title=Notes on the distribution and status of small carnivores in Gabon |journal=Small Carnivore Conservation |volume=48 |pages=19\u201329}}</ref> In Gabon's [[Moukalaba-Doudou National Park]], it was also recorded only in forested areas.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Nakashima, Y. |year=2015 |title=Inventorying medium-and large-sized mammals in the African lowland rainforest using camera trapping |journal=Tropics |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=151\u2013164|doi=10.3759/tropics.23.151 }}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nThe Central African oyan lives foremost in the [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]], but has rarely been observed on the ground. It is [[nocturnal]] and hunts small rodents and birds, but also feeds on insects.<ref name=VanRompaey2013/>\n\nIts breeding habits are unknown.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Whitfield |editor1-first=P. |title=Macmillan Illustrated Animal Encyclopedia |year=1984 |publisher=Macmillan Publishing Company |isbn=0-02-627680-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/macmillanillustr00whit/page/92 92] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/macmillanillustr00whit/page/92 }}</ref><ref name=VanRompaey2013/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe Central African oyan was [[Scientific description|first described]] in 1842 as ''Genetta richardsonii'' by [[T. R. H. Thomson]] based on a [[zoological specimen]] collected in [[Fernando Po (island)|Fernando Po]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomson, T. R. H. |year=1842 |title=Description of a new species of ''Genetta'', and of two species of Birds from Western Africa |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History; Zoology, Botany, and Geology |volume=10 |issue=64 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof10lond/page/202 |pages=203\u2013205|doi=10.1080/03745484209445224 }}</ref>\nIn 1864, [[John Edward Gray]] subordinated it to the genus ''Poiana''.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gray, J. E. |year=1864 |title=A Revision of the Genera and Species of Viverrine Animals (Viverridae) founded on the collection in the British Museum |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |issue= |pages=502\u2013579 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofgen64zool/page/506}}</ref>\n\n==Threats==\nThe Central African oyan is possibly threatened by [[deforestation]] and [[bushmeat]] hunting.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Carnivora|V.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q189978}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:oyan, Central African}}\n[[Category:Viverrids|Central African oyan]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Central Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1842|Central African oyan]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the species of linsang|the genus of linsangs|Poiana (genus)}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Em - Poiana richardsonii 2.jpg\n| name = Central African oyan\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Poiana richardsonii'' |author=Gaubert, P. |author2=Do Linh San, E. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T41704A45219609 |date=2015 |access-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n| taxon = Poiana richardsonii<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000414 |heading=Species ''Poiana richardsonii''}}</ref>\n| authority = [[Thomas Richard Heywood Thomson|Thomson]], 1842\n| range_map = African Linsang area.png\n| range_map_caption = Central African oyan range\n}}\n\nThe '''Central African oyan''' (''Poiana richardsonii''), also called '''Central African linsang''', is a [[Poiana (genus)|linsang]] [[species]] native to [[Central Africa]].<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==Characteristics==\nThe Central African oyan's body is slender and long, with an elongated head and a pointed muzzle. Its fur is yellowish to reddish brown with darker spots on the back and flanks. Its throat and belly are lighter in colour and without spots. Its tail has 9 to 14 dark rings. Its body is {{convert|33-43|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, and the tail about the same length. Its legs are short, and the soles of its feet hairy. Females are slightly smaller than males.<ref name=VanRompaey2013>{{cite book |author=Van Rompaey, H. and Colyn, M. | year=2013 |chapter=''Poiana richardsonii'' Central African Linsang (Central African Oyan) |title=The Mammals of Africa. V. Carnivores, Pangolins, Equids and Rhinoceroses |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London |pages=253\u2212254 |editors=Kingdon, J. and Hoffmann, M. (eds.)}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe Central African oyan is [[endemic]] to [[Cameroon]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Gabon]], the [[Central African Republic]], the [[Republic of the Congo]], and the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] east to the [[Albertine Rift]]. It lives in lowland and montane [[tropical rainforest]]s.<ref name=iucn/>\nIn Gabon, a [[camera-trap]] recorded an individual on the forest floor.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Bahaa-el-din, L., Henschel, P., Aba\u2019a, R., Abernethy, K., Bohm, T., Bout, N., Coad, L., Head, J., Inoue, E., Lahm, S., Lee, M. E., Maisels, F., Rabanal, L., Starkey, M., Taylor, G., Vanthomme, A., Nakashima, Y. and Hunter, L. |year= 2013 |title=Notes on the distribution and status of small carnivores in Gabon |journal=Small Carnivore Conservation |volume=48 |pages=19\u201329}}</ref> In Gabon's [[Moukalaba-Doudou National Park]], it was also recorded only in forested areas.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Nakashima, Y. |year=2015 |title=Inventorying medium-and large-sized mammals in the African lowland rainforest using camera trapping |journal=Tropics |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=151\u2013164|doi=10.3759/tropics.23.151 }}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nThe Central African oyan lives foremost in the [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]], but has rarely been observed on the ground. It is [[nocturnal]] and hunts small rodents and birds, but also feeds on insects.<ref name=VanRompaey2013/>\n\nIts breeding habits are unknown.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Whitfield |editor1-first=P. |title=Macmillan Illustrated Animal Encyclopedia |year=1984 |publisher=Macmillan Publishing Company |isbn=0-02-627680-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/macmillanillustr00whit/page/92 92] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/macmillanillustr00whit/page/92 }}</ref><ref name=VanRompaey2013/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe Central African oyan was [[Scientific description|first described]] in 1842 as ''Genetta richardsonii'' by [[T. R. H. Thomson]] based on a [[zoological specimen]] collected in [[Fernando Po (island)|Fernando Po]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomson, T. R. H. |year=1842 |title=Description of a new species of ''Genetta'', and of two species of Birds from Western Africa |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History; Zoology, Botany, and Geology |volume=10 |issue=64 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof10lond/page/202 |pages=203\u2013205|doi=10.1080/03745484209445224 }}</ref>\nIn 1864, [[John Edward Gray]] subordinated it to the genus ''Poiana''.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gray, J. E. |year=1864 |title=A Revision of the Genera and Species of Viverrine Animals (Viverridae) founded on the collection in the British Museum |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |issue= |pages=502\u2013579 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofgen64zool/page/506}}</ref>\n\n==Threats==\nThe Central African oyan is possibly threatened by [[deforestation]] and [[bushmeat]] hunting.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Carnivora|V.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q189978}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:oyan, Central African}}\n[[Category:Viverrids|Central African oyan]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Central Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1842|Central African oyan]]\n", "name_user": "IznoRepeat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharacteristics:replace soft-deprecated editors parameter, gen fixes, misc cite cleaning", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_African_oyan"}
{"title_page": "Illuminationism", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Divine illumination}}\n'''Illuminationist''' or '''''ishraqi''''' philosophy is a type of [[Islamic philosophy]] introduced by [[Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi]] in the twelfth century CE.\n\n<br />\n==History==\nIlluminationism is an influential school of Islamic Philosophy developed in the 12th century by [[Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi]] (1155&ndash;1191) that is still studied today. Illumination [[Arabic-English Lexicon|(''e\u0161r\u0101q)'']] can be translated as \"the Rising of the Sun.\"  While the 1258 Mongol [[Siege of Baghdad (1258)|Sacking of Baghdad]] and subsequent invasion effectively ended the [[Islamic Golden Age]], it also paved the way for new ideas like illuminationist philosophy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/illuminationism|title=ILLUMINATIONISM \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The Political change brought philosophical changes. \n\nInfluenced by [[Ibn Sina]] and [[Neoplatonism]], the [[Persia]]n<ref>John Walbridge, \u201cThe leaven of the ancients: Suhraward\u012b and the heritage of the Greeks\u201d, State University of New York Press, 1999.  Excerpt: \u201cSuhrawardi, a 12th-century Persian philosopher, was a key figure in the transition of Islamic thought from the neo-Aristotelianism of Avicenna to the mystically oriented philosophy of later centuries.\u201d</ref><ref>Seyyed Hossein Nasr, \u201cThe need for a sacred science\u201d, SUNY Press, 1993.  Pg 158: \u201cPersian philosopher Suhrawardi refers in fact to this land as na-kuja abad,  which in Persian means literally utopia.\u201d</ref><ref>Matthew Kapstein, University of Chicago Press, 2004, \"The presence of light: divine radiance and religious experience\", University of Chicago Press, 2004. pg 285:\"..the light of lights in the system of the Persian philosopher Suhrawardi\"</ref><ref>Hossein Ziai. ''Illuminationsim or Illuminationist philosophy, first introduced in the 12th century as a complete, reconstructed system distinct both from the Peripatetic philosophy of Avicenna and from theological philosophy.'' in: Encyclopaedia Iranica. Volumes XII & XIII. 2004.</ref> or [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]],<ref>{{cite book|last=R. Izady|first=Mehrdad |title=The Kurds: a concise handbook|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1991|url=https://archive.org/details/kurdsconcisehan00izad|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/kurdsconcisehan00izad/page/160 160]|quote=Suhrawardi.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kam\u0101l|first=Mu\u1e25ammad |title=Mulla Sadra's transcendent philosophy|year=2006|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=EwB7Zo7lVp0C&pg=PA12&dq=Suhrawardi+was+a+Kurdish&hl=no&ei=a1MtTubqK8vIsga9wr33Dw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Suhrawardi%20was%20a%20Kurdish&f=false}}</ref><ref>C. E. Butterworth, M. Mahdi, The Political Aspects of Islamic Philosophy, Harvard CMES Publishers, 406 pp., 1992, {{ISBN|0-932885-07-1}} (see p.336)</ref><ref>M. Kamal, Mulla Sadra's Transcendent Philosophy, p.12, Ashgate Publishing Inc., 136 pp., 2006, {{ISBN|0-7546-5271-8}} (see p.12)</ref> philosopher [[Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi]] (1155&ndash;1191), who left over 50 writings in Persian and Arabic, founded the school of Illumination. He developed a version of illuminationism ([[Persian language|Persian]] \u062d\u0643\u0645\u062a \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0642 ''hikmat-i ishr\u0101q'', [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: \u062d\u0643\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0642 ''\u1e25ikmat al-ishr\u0101q''). The Persian and Islamic school draws on ancient [[Iranian philosophy|Iranian philosophical]] disciplines,<ref>Henry Corbin. The Voyage and the Messenger. Iran and Philosophy. Containing previous unpublished articles and lectures from 1948 to 1976. North Atlantic Books. Berkeley, California. 1998. {{ISBN|1-55643-269-0}}.</ref><ref>Henry Corbin. The Man of Light in Iranian Sufism. Omega Publications, New York. 1994. {{ISBN|0-930872-48-7}}.</ref> Avicennism ([[Avicenna|Ibn Sina]]\u2019s [[early Islamic philosophy]]), [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonic]] thought (modified by Ibn Sina), and the original ideas of Suhrawardi.\n\nNone of Suhrawardi's works were translated into Latin, and so he remained unknown in the [[Latin West]], although his work continued to be studied in the Islamic East.<ref>Marcotte, Roxanne, \"Suhrawardi\", The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Summer 2012 Edition), Edward N. Zalta (ed.), URL = <http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2012/entries/suhrawardi/>.</ref>\nAccording to [[Hosein Nasr]], Suhrawardi was unknown to the west until he was translated to western languages by contemporary thinkers such as [[Henry Corbin]], and he remains largely unknown even in countries within the Islamic world.<ref>{{harvnb|Hosein Nasr|1997|p=55|three muslin sages}}</ref> Suhrawardi tried to present a new perspective on questions like those of existence. He not only caused peripatetic philosophers to confront such new questions but also gave new life to the body of philosophy after Avicenna.<ref>{{harvnb|Nasr|2006|p=86|Islamic philosophy from its origin to the present}}</ref>  According to John Walbridge, Suhrawardi's critiques of [[Peripatetic philosophy]] could be counted as an important turning point for his successors. Although Suhravardi was first a pioneer of Peripatetic philosophy, he later became a Platonist following a mystical experience. He is also counted as one who revived the ancient wisdom in Persia by his philosophy of illumination. His followers, such as Shahrzouri and [[Qutb al-Din al-Shirazi]] tried to continue the way of their teacher. Suhrewardi makes a distinction between two approaches in the philosophy of illumination: one approach is discursive and another is intuitive.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Walbridge|title=The Cambridge Companion to Arabic Philosophy|date=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780511999864|editor-last1=Adamson|editor-first1=Peter|pp=201\u2013223|chapter=Suhraward\u012b and Illuminationism|editor-last2=Taylor|editor-first2=Richard C.}} </ref>\n\nIlluminationist thinkers in the [[School of Isfahan]] played a significant role in revitalizing academic life in the <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://associationforiranianstudies.org/node/149|title=Safavid- Mughal Cultural Interrelations as reflected in Matenadaran\u2019s \u2018Bayaz\u2019 Manuscript Illumination {{!}} Association for Iranian Studies (AIS) {{!}} \u0627\u0646\u062c\u0645\u0646 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\u200c \u067e\u0698\u0648\u0647\u06cc|website=associationforiranianstudies.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> [[Safavid empire|Safavid]] Empire under Shah [[Abbas the Great|Abbas]] I. (1588-1629) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Avicennan thought continued to inform philosophy during the reign of the Safavid Empire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Illuminationism was taught in Safavid [[Madrasa|Madrasas]] (Place of Study) established by pious shahs. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/29816/11/Moazzen_Maryam_2011_PhD_thesis.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Early Modern Age Illuminationism ==\n'''[[Mulla Sadra]] (\u1e62adr ad-D\u012bn Mu\u1e25ammad Sh\u012br\u0101z\u012b) 17th century Iranian philosopher was considered a master'''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Aminrazavi|first=Mehdi Amin Razavi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRsiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA137&lpg=PA137&dq=mulla+sadra+illumination&source=bl&ots=6Wz9EV07Tq&sig=ACfU3U2htwbdPHs9DmI2_447a0tqq2i3YQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjoh4HfqN3oAhVFKH0KHbKIB_IQ6AEwB3oECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=mulla%20sadra%20illumination&f=false|title=Suhrawardi and the School of Illumination|date=2014-03-18|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-79281-6|language=en}}</ref> '''of illuminationism. He''' wrote a book titled al-Asfar meaning \"The Yellow\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.byuh.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://www.jstor.org%2fstable%2f1595794%3fSearch%3dyes%26resultItemClick%3dtrue%26searchText%3dal-asfar%26searchUri%3d%2faction%2fdoBasicSearch%3fQuery%3dal-asfar%26amp%3bacc%3don%26amp%3bwc%3don%26amp%3bfc%3doff%26amp%3bgroup%3dnone%26ab_segments%3d0%2fbasic_SYC-5152%2fcontrol%26refreqid%3dsearch%3a1837e09e34b62f9037208fc08081f6a8%26seq%3d1|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.byuh.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> or \"The Light.\" The word Asfar also denotes a journey of the soul back to Allah. He developed his book into an entire School of Thought, he did not refer to al-Asfar as a philosophy but as [http://www.mullasadra.org/new_site/English/Mullasadra/Methodology.htm \"wisdom.\"] Sadra taught how one could be illuminated or given wisdom until becoming a sage.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rizvi|first=Sajjad|title=Mulla Sadra|date=2019|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2019/entries/mulla-sadra/|work=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|edition=Spring 2019|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Al-Asfar was one piece of '''[[Illuminationism]] which is still an active part of [[Islamic philosophy|Islaamic Philosophy]] today. Al-Asfar was representative of Mulla Sadra's entire philosophical worldview.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/MuhammadKamalMullaSadrasTranscendentPhilosBookZZ.org/%5BMuhammad_Kamal%5D_Mulla_Sadra%27s_Transcendent_Philos(BookZZ.org)_djvu.txt|title=Full text of \"Mulla Sadra's Transcendent Philosophy\"|website=archive.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>Like many important Arabian works it is difficult for the western world to understand because it has not been translated into English. Mulla Sadra eventually became the most significant teacher at the religious school known as Madrasa-yi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>[https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/29816/11/Moazzen_Maryam_2011_PhD_thesis.pdf (Royal School.)] His philosophies are still taught throughout the Islamic East and South South Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\n== Key Concepts ==\nIn his ''Philosophy of Illumination'', Suhrawardi argued that light operates at all levels and hierarchies of reality (PI, 97.7&ndash;98.11). Light produces immaterial and substantial lights, including immaterial intellects ([[angel]]s), human and animal souls, and even 'dusky substances', such as bodies.<ref>''Philosophy of Illumination'' 77.1&ndash;78.9</ref>\n\nSuhrawardi's metaphysics is based on two principles.  The first is a form of the [[principle of sufficient reason]]. The second principle is Aristotle's principle that an [[actual infinity]] is impossible.<ref>''Philosophy of Illumination'' 87.1&ndash;89.8</ref> \n\n== Illuminationism in Books ==\n'''Al-Asfar is [[Mulla Sadra|Mulla Sadra's]] book explaining his view of illuminationism. He views problems starting with a [[Peripatetic school|Peripatetic sketch.]]''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mullasadra.org/new_site/English/Mullasadra/Methodology.htm|title=Methodology|last=SIPR|first=|date=|website=MullaSadra.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This Aristotelian style of teaching is reminiscent of [[Islamic Golden Age]] Philosopher [[Avicenna]]. Mulla Sadra often refers to the Qur'an when dealing with philosophical problems. He even quotes Qur'anic verses while explaining philosophy. He wrote [[Tafasir Al Quran|exegeses]] of the Qur'an such as his explanation of [http://en.wikishia.net/view/Mulla_Sadra%27s_Exegesis_of_the_Qur%27an_(book) Al-Kursi.]\n\nAsfar means journey. In al-Asfar you are gaining on a journey to gain wisdom. Mulla Sadra used philosophy as a set spiritual exercises to become more wise. Eventually this as you go through life you continue to gain more knowledge until you become a sage, hence godlike.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rizvi|first=Sajjad|title=Mulla Sadra|date=2019|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2019/entries/mulla-sadra/|work=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|edition=Spring 2019|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn Mulla Sadra's book '''''[[The Transcendent Philosophy of the Four Journeys of the Intellect]]''''' he describes the four journeys of\n\n1. A journey from creation to the Truth or [[Allah|Creator]]\n\n2.  A journey from the Truth to the Truth\n\n3. A journey that stands in relation to the first journey because it is from the Truth to creation with the Truth\n\n4. A journey that stands in relation to the second journey because it is from the Truth to the creation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/MuhammadKamalMullaSadrasTranscendentPhilosBookZZ.org/%5BMuhammad_Kamal%5D_Mulla_Sadra%27s_Transcendent_Philos(BookZZ.org)_djvu.txt|title=Full text of \"Mulla Sadra's Transcendent Philosophy\"|website=archive.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n\n<!--Important, do not remove this line before article has been created.--><br />\n\n* [[Light (theology)]]\n* [[Mulla Sadra]]\n* [[Enlightenment (spiritual)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Suhrawardi and the School of Illumination'' by Mehdi Amin Razavi\n* ''Islamic Intellectual Tradition in Persia'' by [[Seyyed Hossein Nasr]]\n\n==External links==\n* \"\", Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy\n* \n\n{{philosophy topics|schools}}\n\n[[Category:Persian philosophy]]\n[[Category:History of logic]]\n[[Category:Theories of deduction]]\n[[Category:Iranian philosophy]]\n[[fr:Philosophie illuminative]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Divine illumination}}\n'''Illuminationist''' or '''''ishraqi''''' philosophy is a type of [[Islamic philosophy]] introduced by [[Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi]] in the twelfth century CE.\n\n<br />\n==History==\nIlluminationism is an influential school of Islamic Philosophy developed in the 12th century by [[Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi]] (1155&ndash;1191) that is still studied today. Illumination [[Arabic-English Lexicon|(''e\u0161r\u0101q)'']] can be translated as \"the Rising of the Sun.\"  While the 1258 Mongol [[Siege of Baghdad (1258)|Sacking of Baghdad]] and subsequent invasion effectively ended the [[Islamic Golden Age]], it also paved the way for new ideas like illuminationist philosophy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/illuminationism|title=ILLUMINATIONISM \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The Political change brought philosophical changes. \n\nInfluenced by [[Ibn Sina]] and [[Neoplatonism]], the [[Persia]]n<ref>John Walbridge, \u201cThe leaven of the ancients: Suhraward\u012b and the heritage of the Greeks\u201d, State University of New York Press, 1999.  Excerpt: \u201cSuhrawardi, a 12th-century Persian philosopher, was a key figure in the transition of Islamic thought from the neo-Aristotelianism of Avicenna to the mystically oriented philosophy of later centuries.\u201d</ref><ref>Seyyed Hossein Nasr, \u201cThe need for a sacred science\u201d, SUNY Press, 1993.  Pg 158: \u201cPersian philosopher Suhrawardi refers in fact to this land as na-kuja abad,  which in Persian means literally utopia.\u201d</ref><ref>Matthew Kapstein, University of Chicago Press, 2004, \"The presence of light: divine radiance and religious experience\", University of Chicago Press, 2004. pg 285:\"..the light of lights in the system of the Persian philosopher Suhrawardi\"</ref><ref>Hossein Ziai. ''Illuminationsim or Illuminationist philosophy, first introduced in the 12th century as a complete, reconstructed system distinct both from the Peripatetic philosophy of Avicenna and from theological philosophy.'' in: Encyclopaedia Iranica. Volumes XII & XIII. 2004.</ref> or [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]],<ref>{{cite book|last=R. Izady|first=Mehrdad |title=The Kurds: a concise handbook|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1991|url=https://archive.org/details/kurdsconcisehan00izad|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/kurdsconcisehan00izad/page/160 160]|quote=Suhrawardi.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kam\u0101l|first=Mu\u1e25ammad |title=Mulla Sadra's transcendent philosophy|year=2006|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=EwB7Zo7lVp0C&pg=PA12&dq=Suhrawardi+was+a+Kurdish&hl=no&ei=a1MtTubqK8vIsga9wr33Dw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Suhrawardi%20was%20a%20Kurdish&f=false}}</ref><ref>C. E. Butterworth, M. Mahdi, The Political Aspects of Islamic Philosophy, Harvard CMES Publishers, 406 pp., 1992, {{ISBN|0-932885-07-1}} (see p.336)</ref><ref>M. Kamal, Mulla Sadra's Transcendent Philosophy, p.12, Ashgate Publishing Inc., 136 pp., 2006, {{ISBN|0-7546-5271-8}} (see p.12)</ref> philosopher [[Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi]] (1155&ndash;1191), who left over 50 writings in Persian and Arabic, founded the school of Illumination. He developed a version of illuminationism ([[Persian language|Persian]] \u062d\u0643\u0645\u062a \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0642 ''hikmat-i ishr\u0101q'', [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: \u062d\u0643\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0642 ''\u1e25ikmat al-ishr\u0101q''). The Persian and Islamic school draws on ancient [[Iranian philosophy|Iranian philosophical]] disciplines,<ref>Henry Corbin. The Voyage and the Messenger. Iran and Philosophy. Containing previous unpublished articles and lectures from 1948 to 1976. North Atlantic Books. Berkeley, California. 1998. {{ISBN|1-55643-269-0}}.</ref><ref>Henry Corbin. The Man of Light in Iranian Sufism. Omega Publications, New York. 1994. {{ISBN|0-930872-48-7}}.</ref> Avicennism ([[Avicenna|Ibn Sina]]\u2019s [[early Islamic philosophy]]), [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonic]] thought (modified by Ibn Sina), and the original ideas of Suhrawardi.\n\nNone of Suhrawardi's works were translated into Latin, and so he remained unknown in the [[Latin West]], although his work continued to be studied in the Islamic East.<ref>Marcotte, Roxanne, \"Suhrawardi\", The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Summer 2012 Edition), Edward N. Zalta (ed.), URL = <http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2012/entries/suhrawardi/>.</ref>\nAccording to [[Hosein Nasr]], Suhrawardi was unknown to the west until he was translated to western languages by contemporary thinkers such as [[Henry Corbin]], and he remains largely unknown even in countries within the Islamic world.<ref>{{harvnb|Hosein Nasr|1997|p=55|three muslin sages}}</ref> Suhrawardi tried to present a new perspective on questions like those of existence. He not only caused peripatetic philosophers to confront such new questions but also gave new life to the body of philosophy after Avicenna.<ref>{{harvnb|Nasr|2006|p=86|Islamic philosophy from its origin to the present}}</ref>  According to John Walbridge, Suhrawardi's critiques of [[Peripatetic philosophy]] could be counted as an important turning point for his successors. Although Suhravardi was first a pioneer of Peripatetic philosophy, he later became a Platonist following a mystical experience. He is also counted as one who revived the ancient wisdom in Persia by his philosophy of illumination. His followers, such as Shahrzouri and [[Qutb al-Din al-Shirazi]] tried to continue the way of their teacher. Suhrewardi makes a distinction between two approaches in the philosophy of illumination: one approach is discursive and another is intuitive.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Walbridge|title=The Cambridge Companion to Arabic Philosophy|date=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780511999864|editor-last1=Adamson|editor-first1=Peter|pp=201\u2013223|chapter=Suhraward\u012b and Illuminationism|editor-last2=Taylor|editor-first2=Richard C.}} </ref>\n\nIlluminationist thinkers in the the [[School of Isfahan]] played a significant role in revitalizing academic life in the <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://associationforiranianstudies.org/node/149|title=Safavid- Mughal Cultural Interrelations as reflected in Matenadaran\u2019s \u2018Bayaz\u2019 Manuscript Illumination {{!}} Association for Iranian Studies (AIS) {{!}} \u0627\u0646\u062c\u0645\u0646 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\u200c \u067e\u0698\u0648\u0647\u06cc|website=associationforiranianstudies.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> [[Safavid empire|Safavid]] Empire under Shah [[Abbas the Great|Abbas]] I. (1588-1629) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Avicennan thought continued to inform philosophy during the reign of the Safavid Empire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Illuminationism was taught in Safavid [[Madrasa|Madrasas]] (Place of Study) established by pious shahs. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/29816/11/Moazzen_Maryam_2011_PhD_thesis.pdf|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Early Modern Age Illuminationism ==\n'''[[Mulla Sadra]] (\u1e62adr ad-D\u012bn Mu\u1e25ammad Sh\u012br\u0101z\u012b) 17th century Iranian philosopher was considered a master'''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Aminrazavi|first=Mehdi Amin Razavi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRsiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA137&lpg=PA137&dq=mulla+sadra+illumination&source=bl&ots=6Wz9EV07Tq&sig=ACfU3U2htwbdPHs9DmI2_447a0tqq2i3YQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjoh4HfqN3oAhVFKH0KHbKIB_IQ6AEwB3oECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=mulla%20sadra%20illumination&f=false|title=Suhrawardi and the School of Illumination|date=2014-03-18|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-79281-6|language=en}}</ref> '''of illuminationism. He''' wrote a book titled al-Asfar meaning \"The Yellow\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.byuh.idm.oclc.org/login?qurl=https://www.jstor.org%2fstable%2f1595794%3fSearch%3dyes%26resultItemClick%3dtrue%26searchText%3dal-asfar%26searchUri%3d%2faction%2fdoBasicSearch%3fQuery%3dal-asfar%26amp%3bacc%3don%26amp%3bwc%3don%26amp%3bfc%3doff%26amp%3bgroup%3dnone%26ab_segments%3d0%2fbasic_SYC-5152%2fcontrol%26refreqid%3dsearch%3a1837e09e34b62f9037208fc08081f6a8%26seq%3d1|title=Shibboleth Authentication Request|website=login.byuh.idm.oclc.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> or \"The Light.\" The word Asfar also denotes a journey of the soul back to Allah. He developed his book into an entire School of Thought, he did not refer to al-Asfar as a philosophy but as [http://www.mullasadra.org/new_site/English/Mullasadra/Methodology.htm \"wisdom.\"] Sadra taught how one could be illuminated or given wisdom until becoming a sage.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rizvi|first=Sajjad|title=Mulla Sadra|date=2019|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2019/entries/mulla-sadra/|work=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|edition=Spring 2019|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Al-Asfar was one piece of '''[[Illuminationism]] which is still an active part of [[Islamic philosophy|Islaamic Philosophy]] today. Al-Asfar was representative of Mulla Sadra's entire philosophical worldview.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/MuhammadKamalMullaSadrasTranscendentPhilosBookZZ.org/%5BMuhammad_Kamal%5D_Mulla_Sadra%27s_Transcendent_Philos(BookZZ.org)_djvu.txt|title=Full text of \"Mulla Sadra's Transcendent Philosophy\"|website=archive.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>Like many important Arabian works it is difficult for the western world to understand because it has not been translated into English. Mulla Sadra eventually became the most significant teacher at the religious school known as Madrasa-yi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>[https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/29816/11/Moazzen_Maryam_2011_PhD_thesis.pdf (Royal School.)] His philosophies are still taught throughout the Islamic East and South South Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leibniz.stanford.edu/friends/preview/mulla-sadra/|title=Friends of the SEP Society - Preview of Mulla Sadra PDF|website=leibniz.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\n== Key Concepts ==\nIn his ''Philosophy of Illumination'', Suhrawardi argued that light operates at all levels and hierarchies of reality (PI, 97.7&ndash;98.11). Light produces immaterial and substantial lights, including immaterial intellects ([[angel]]s), human and animal souls, and even 'dusky substances', such as bodies.<ref>''Philosophy of Illumination'' 77.1&ndash;78.9</ref>\n\nSuhrawardi's metaphysics is based on two principles.  The first is a form of the [[principle of sufficient reason]]. The second principle is Aristotle's principle that an [[actual infinity]] is impossible.<ref>''Philosophy of Illumination'' 87.1&ndash;89.8</ref> \n\n== Illuminationism in Books ==\n'''Al-Asfar is [[Mulla Sadra|Mulla Sadra's]] book explaining his view of illuminationism. He views problems starting with a [[Peripatetic school|Peripatetic sketch.]]''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mullasadra.org/new_site/English/Mullasadra/Methodology.htm|title=Methodology|last=SIPR|first=|date=|website=MullaSadra.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This Aristotelian style of teaching is reminiscent of [[Islamic Golden Age]] Philosopher [[Avicenna]]. Mulla Sadra often refers to the Qur'an when dealing with philosophical problems. He even quotes Qur'anic verses while explaining philosophy. He wrote [[Tafasir Al Quran|exegeses]] of the Qur'an such as his explanation of [http://en.wikishia.net/view/Mulla_Sadra%27s_Exegesis_of_the_Qur%27an_(book) Al-Kursi.]\n\nAsfar means journey. In al-Asfar you are gaining on a journey to gain wisdom. Mulla Sadra used philosophy as a set spiritual exercises to become more wise. Eventually this as you go through life you continue to gain more knowledge until you become a sage, hence godlike.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rizvi|first=Sajjad|title=Mulla Sadra|date=2019|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2019/entries/mulla-sadra/|work=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|edition=Spring 2019|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn Mulla Sadra's book '''''[[The Transcendent Philosophy of the Four Journeys of the Intellect]]''''' he describes the four journeys of\n\n1. A journey from creation to the Truth or [[Allah|Creator]]\n\n2.  A journey from the Truth to the Truth\n\n3. A journey that stands in relation to the first journey because it is from the Truth to creation with the Truth\n\n4. A journey that stands in relation to the second journey because it is from the Truth to the creation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/MuhammadKamalMullaSadrasTranscendentPhilosBookZZ.org/%5BMuhammad_Kamal%5D_Mulla_Sadra%27s_Transcendent_Philos(BookZZ.org)_djvu.txt|title=Full text of \"Mulla Sadra's Transcendent Philosophy\"|website=archive.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n\n<!--Important, do not remove this line before article has been created.--><br />\n\n* [[Light (theology)]]\n* [[Mulla Sadra]]\n* [[Enlightenment (spiritual)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Suhrawardi and the School of Illumination'' by Mehdi Amin Razavi\n* ''Islamic Intellectual Tradition in Persia'' by [[Seyyed Hossein Nasr]]\n\n==External links==\n* \"\", Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy\n* \n\n{{philosophy topics|schools}}\n\n[[Category:Persian philosophy]]\n[[Category:History of logic]]\n[[Category:Theories of deduction]]\n[[Category:Iranian philosophy]]\n[[fr:Philosophie illuminative]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Illuminationism"}
{"title_page": "Jane Davis Doggett", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          =\n| image         = 1960s_Jane_Davis_Doggett_in_the_studio.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       =Jane Davis Doggett, ca. 1960s\n| birth_name    =Jane Davis Doggett\n| birth_date    ={{Birth date|df=y|1929|11|04}}\n| birth_place   =[[Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], US\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   =[[US]]\n| field         =[[Graphic Design]], [[Wayfinding]]\n| training      =[[H. Sophie Newcomb Memorial College|Sophie Newcomb College]], [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana|LA]], 1952<br />\n[[Yale University|Yale]] School of Graphic Design\n| movement      = \n| spouse        = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Jane Davis Doggett''' (born 1929) is a graphic artist and pioneer designer of wayfinding and graphics systems for airports.<ref name=\"florida-DOS\">{{cite web|title=Jane Davis Doggett|url=http://dos.myflorida.com/cultural/programs/florida-artists-hall-of-fame/jane-davis-doggett/|website=Florida Department of State|publisher=Division of Cultural Affairs|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\n\nDoggett grew up in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]].  She graduated from Sophie Newcomb College (Tulane University, New Orleans, LA) in 1952<ref name=\"Tulane Newcomb Alumnae\">{{cite web|title=Outstanding Alumna Jane Davis Doggett: graphics design pioneer|url=http://tulane.edu/newcomb-alumnae/oaks/upload/UTO_S08.pdf|accessdate=April 7, 2014|page=4}}</ref>  and [[Yale University]] [[Yale School of Art|School of Art and Architecture]] in 1956 with an MFA in graphics, where she worked under noted colorist [[Josef Albers]], who had recently been appointed Head of Yale's Graphic Design department. \"As an early student of Josef Albers, she took his famed Interaction of Color course and absorbed Albers\u2019 inspired principles of color perception while establishing her own strong artistic identity.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 SEGD Fellow and Achievement Award Winners Announced: Jane Davis Doggett |url=https://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett |publisher=Society for Experiential Graphic Design |location=Washington, DC |date=2018}}</ref>\n\nHer first job after graduate school was with [[George Nelson (designer)|George Nelson]], working on the anthropological part of the permanent exhibit at [[Colonial Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]].  She then worked in Europe for the magazine [[Architectural Record]], photographing architects and engineers and their work.  Her first airport design job was for the [[Memphis International Airport|Memphis airport]] in 1959.  The project\u2019s architect Roy Harrover knew Doggett from both Nashville and Yale and brought her in to do the graphics.  Her first innovation was the development of a standardized font for use throughout the airport.  This font became Doggett\u2019s trademarked \u201cAlphabet A\u201d and was used in many subsequent airport projects, since it was very readable over long distances.<ref name=\"Experiential Graphics Magazine\">{{cite journal|last2=Knapp |last1=Turner |first2=Pat Matson |first1=Tracy|title=Jane Davis Doggett, Environmental Graphics Pioneer |journal=Experiential Graphics Magazine |volume=5 |date=2013 |url=http://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett-environmental-graphics-pioneer}}</ref>\nAdditional airport projects included [[Tampa International Airport|Tampa International]], [[George Bush Intercontinental Airport|George Bush-Houston]], [[Baltimore\u2013Washington International Airport|Baltimore-Washington]], [[Newark Liberty International Airport|Newark]], [[Miami International Airport|Miami]], [[Fort Lauderdale\u2013Hollywood International Airport|Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood]], and [[Cleveland Hopkins International Airport|Cleveland-Hopkins]] among others.\n\nAs of 2014, Doggett had designed wayfinding systems for 40 major airport projects,<ref name=\"Yale\">{{cite web|last=Yale Art Gallery|title=Jane Davis Doggett Talking Graphics|url=http://artgallery.yale.edu/exhibitions/exhibition/jane-davis-doggett-talking-graphics}}</ref> which is said to be \u201cmore than any other designer in the world.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Elliott Museum|title=Albers and Heirs Exhibit|url=http://elliottmuseumfl.org/albers-and-heirs-exhibit.htm}}</ref> Each year, 20 million airplane passengers are guided by her way-finding signage and graphics.<ref name=\"Ellsworth American\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jddinc.com/2011/article-taming-chaos.html|title=Taming Chaos: Corea Artist Pioneered Nation's Airport Graphics|last=Weaver|first=Jacqueline|date=September 26, 2013|newspaper=Ellsworth American, Ellsworth, ME|access-date=February 13, 2017|at=Section III, Page 5}}</ref>\n\nDoggett is credited with four innovations that are now commonly employed in airports and other large public spaces:\n* Use of color,<ref name=\"New York Times Magazine\">{{cite news|last=Conniff|first=James C. G.|title=Danger: Signs Ahead|newspaper=New York Times Magazine|date=March 30, 1975|page=36}}</ref>  letter, and symbol<ref name=\"Ellsworth American\" />  to guide visitors through large unfamiliar places.\n* Designs that begin on highways outside the structure, simplifying and making the wayfinding process safer for drivers<ref name=\"eg Experiential Graphics Magazine\">{{cite journal|last=Knapp|first=Pat Matson|year=2013|title=Jane Davis Doggett: Environmental Graphics Pioneer|url=http://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett-environmental-graphics-pioneer|journal=Eg Experiential Graphics Magazine|volume=No. 07|page=50|via=|author2=Turner, Tracy|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>  or other travelers while also reducing the number of signs needed.  Doggett's system eliminated two-thirds of the highway signs that had originally been proposed for the Tampa airport.<ref name=\"New York Times Magazine\"/>\n* Building the verbal or symbolic message into the architecture rather than tacking it on as a sign.\n* Creating a visual symbol to brand the airport and represent it as a gateway to the surrounding region.<ref name=\"Experiential Graphics Magazine\" />\n\nOther notable graphics and design projects that she has worked on include [[Madison Square Garden]], the [[Philadelphia]] subway system,<ref name=\"New York Times Magazine\"/> the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], [[Niagara Falls]] International Convention Center, [[Jones Hall for the Performing Arts]] in [[Houston]], and Fairfax Hospital in Virginia.  Doggett\u2019s designs have been awarded the [[American Institute of Architects]]\u2019 National Award of Merit, the Progressive Architecture Design Award,<ref name=\"Tulane Newcomb Alumnae\" />  American Iron and Steel Institute's Design in Steel Citation, and two Design Awards co-sponsored by the [[U.S. Department of Transportation]] and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]].{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nIn her fine art work since 2007, Doggett has developed the concept of the Iconochrome,  which she has described as \u201cgeometric designs in colors expressing philosophically profound messages.\u201d<ref name=\"Yale\" /> She has also described an Iconochrome as a colorful image or \u201cIcon, an image with meaning, plus chrome, color.\u201d<ref name=\"The Tennessean\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=MiChelle|title=Artist Interprets Proverbs through Talking Graphics|newspaper=The Tennessean (Sunday Arts and Entertainment section, Nashville, TN)|date=Oct 4, 2009}}</ref> Her work has been exhibited at the [[Yale University Art Gallery]].;<ref name=\"Yale\" /><ref name=\"Art Daily 1\">{{cite web|title=Special Installation Showcases Unique \"Visual Language\" Depicting Timeless Philosophical Messages|url=http://artdaily.com/news/35777/Special-Installation-Showcases-Unique--Visual-Language--Depicting-Timeless-Philosophical-Messages#.Uxla017WSXU.|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2010/01/26/yuag-features-signs-as-art |title=YUAG features signs as art |publisher=Yale Daily News |date=2010-01-26 |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref> [[Tennessee State Museum]], Nashville; Armory Art Center, West Palm Beach, FL; Tampa International Airport; Lighthouse Art Center, Tequesta, FL; Northern Trust, North Palm Beach, FL; Maritime and Classic Boat Museum, Jensen Beach, FL; Chapter Two, Corea, ME; [[College of the Atlantic]], Bar Harbor, ME;<ref name=\"College of the Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=http://news.coa.edu/2012/07/01/doggetts-bold-graphics/|title=Doggett's Bold Graphics|last=Gold|first=Donna|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> Littlefield Gallery, Winter Harbor, ME;<ref name=\"Ellsworth American\" /> [[Elliott Museum]], Stuart, FL.<ref name=\"Art Daily 2\">{{cite web|title=Josef Albers and Heirs exhibit on view at The Elliott Museum in Florida|url=http://artdaily.com/news/67080/Josef-Albers-and-Heirs-exhibit-on-view-at-The-Elliot-Museum-in-Florida#.UxlYk17WSXU|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://martincountytimes.com/elliott-museum-presents-albers-heirs-josef-albers-neil-welliver-and-jane-davis-doggett |title=Elliott Museum presents 'Albers & Heirs: Josef Albers, Neil Welliver, and Jane Davis Doggett' |work=Martin County Times |publisher=Martincountytimes.com |date=2013-11-09 |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"250\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:2018 Jane Davis Doggett Wayfinder Designs, Tampa Airport Exhibition.jpg|''Coding by Color, Letter, and Symbol,'' Jane Davis Doggett, ca. 1962.</br>Tampa Bay Airport Exhibition, 2014<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=Coding by Color, Letter, and Symbol |url=https://i.imgur.com/2cFQy6K.jpg |publisher=Tampa Bay Airport}}</ref>\nFile:1960 Jane Davis Doggett Terminal Design.jpg|Baltimore-Washington International Airport, Jane Davis Doggett, ca. 1960.</br? Doggett used airport logos as unifying graphic elements.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=Baltimore-Washington International Terminal Design |url=https://segd.org/sites/default/files/styles/galleryformatter_slide/public/30210001_0.jpg?itok=payOHTCm |publisher=Society for Experiential Graphic Design |date=2014}}</ref>\nFile:2012 Jane Davis Doggett, Knockabouts off Dixon Point.jpg|''Knockabouts off Dixon Point,'' Jane Davis Doggett, 2012.<br/>Later graphic work<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=Knockabouts off Dixon Point |url=https://www.ellsworthamerican.com/living/arts-a-living/doggett-offers-graphics-that-grab-the-eye-at-blum/ |publisher=Ellsworth American |date=2012}}</ref>\nFile:2007 Twenty-Third Psalm For The Twenty-First Century, sculpture by Jane Davis Doggett.jpg|''The Twenty-Third Psalm,'' Jane Davis Doggett, 2012. Final Panel: \"And I will dwell in the house of the Lord forever.\"<br/>Saint Thomas More Chapel & Center, Yale University, New HaveN, CT<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=The Twenty-Third Psalm |url=https://stm.yale.edu/23rd-psalm |publisher=Yale University |location=New Haven, CT |date=2012}}</ref> \n</gallery>\n\n==Awards & Honors==\n:2016: inducted into the [[Florida Artists Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dos.myflorida.com/cultural/programs/florida-artists-hall-of-fame/|title=Florida Artists Hall of Fame - Division of Cultural Affairs - Florida Department of State|website=dos.myflorida.com|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n:2018: Society for Experiential Graphic Design Fellow<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 SEGD Fellow: Jane David Doggett |url=https://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett |publisher=SEGD |location=Washington, DC |date=2018}}</ref>\n\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doggett, Jane Davis}}\n[[Category:Yale School of Art alumni]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          =\n| image         = 1960s_Jane_Davis_Doggett_in_the_studio.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       =Jane Davis Doggett, ca. 1960s\n| birth_name    =Jane Davis Doggett\n| birth_date    ={{Birth date|df=y|1929|11|04}}\n| birth_place   =[[Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], US\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   =[[US]]\n| field         =[[Graphic Design]], [[Wayfinding]]\n| training      =[[H. Sophie Newcomb Memorial College|Sophie Newcomb College]], [[New Orleans]], [[LA]], 1952<br />\n[[Yale University|Yale]] School of Graphic Design\n| movement      = \n| spouse        = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Jane Davis Doggett''' (born 1929) is a graphic artist and pioneer designer of wayfinding and graphics systems for airports.<ref name=\"florida-DOS\">{{cite web|title=Jane Davis Doggett|url=http://dos.myflorida.com/cultural/programs/florida-artists-hall-of-fame/jane-davis-doggett/|website=Florida Department of State|publisher=Division of Cultural Affairs|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\n\nDoggett grew up in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]].  She graduated from Sophie Newcomb College (Tulane University, New Orleans, LA) in 1952<ref name=\"Tulane Newcomb Alumnae\">{{cite web|title=Outstanding Alumna Jane Davis Doggett: graphics design pioneer|url=http://tulane.edu/newcomb-alumnae/oaks/upload/UTO_S08.pdf|accessdate=April 7, 2014|page=4}}</ref>  and [[Yale University]] [[Yale School of Art|School of Art and Architecture]] in 1956 with an MFA in graphics, where she worked under noted colorist [[Josef Albers]], who had recently been appointed Head of Yale's Graphic Design department. \"As an early student of Josef Albers, she took his famed Interaction of Color course and absorbed Albers\u2019 inspired principles of color perception while establishing her own strong artistic identity.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 SEGD Fellow and Achievement Award Winners Announced: Jane Davis Doggett |url=https://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett |publisher=Society for Experiential Graphic Design |location=Washington, DC |date=2018}}</ref>\n\nHer first job after graduate school was with [[George Nelson (designer)|George Nelson]], working on the anthropological part of the permanent exhibit at [[Colonial Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]].  She then worked in Europe for the magazine [[Architectural Record]], photographing architects and engineers and their work.  Her first airport design job was for the [[Memphis International Airport|Memphis airport]] in 1959.  The project\u2019s architect Roy Harrover knew Doggett from both Nashville and Yale and brought her in to do the graphics.  Her first innovation was the development of a standardized font for use throughout the airport.  This font became Doggett\u2019s trademarked \u201cAlphabet A\u201d and was used in many subsequent airport projects, since it was very readable over long distances.<ref name=\"Experiential Graphics Magazine\">{{cite journal|last2=Knapp |last1=Turner |first2=Pat Matson |first1=Tracy|title=Jane Davis Doggett, Environmental Graphics Pioneer |journal=Experiential Graphics Magazine |volume=5 |date=2013 |url=http://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett-environmental-graphics-pioneer}}</ref>\nAdditional airport projects included [[Tampa International Airport|Tampa International]], [[George Bush Intercontinental Airport|George Bush-Houston]], [[Baltimore\u2013Washington International Airport|Baltimore-Washington]], [[Newark Liberty International Airport|Newark]], [[Miami International Airport|Miami]], [[Fort Lauderdale\u2013Hollywood International Airport|Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood]], and [[Cleveland Hopkins International Airport|Cleveland-Hopkins]] among others.\n\nAs of 2014, Doggett had designed wayfinding systems for 40 major airport projects,<ref name=\"Yale\">{{cite web|last=Yale Art Gallery|title=Jane Davis Doggett Talking Graphics|url=http://artgallery.yale.edu/exhibitions/exhibition/jane-davis-doggett-talking-graphics}}</ref> which is said to be \u201cmore than any other designer in the world.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Elliott Museum|title=Albers and Heirs Exhibit|url=http://elliottmuseumfl.org/albers-and-heirs-exhibit.htm}}</ref> Each year, 20 million airplane passengers are guided by her way-finding signage and graphics.<ref name=\"Ellsworth American\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jddinc.com/2011/article-taming-chaos.html|title=Taming Chaos: Corea Artist Pioneered Nation's Airport Graphics|last=Weaver|first=Jacqueline|date=September 26, 2013|newspaper=Ellsworth American, Ellsworth, ME|access-date=February 13, 2017|at=Section III, Page 5}}</ref>\n\nDoggett is credited with four innovations that are now commonly employed in airports and other large public spaces:\n* Use of color,<ref name=\"New York Times Magazine\">{{cite news|last=Conniff|first=James C. G.|title=Danger: Signs Ahead|newspaper=New York Times Magazine|date=March 30, 1975|page=36}}</ref>  letter, and symbol<ref name=\"Ellsworth American\" />  to guide visitors through large unfamiliar places.\n* Designs that begin on highways outside the structure, simplifying and making the wayfinding process safer for drivers<ref name=\"eg Experiential Graphics Magazine\">{{cite journal|last=Knapp|first=Pat Matson|year=2013|title=Jane Davis Doggett: Environmental Graphics Pioneer|url=http://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett-environmental-graphics-pioneer|journal=Eg Experiential Graphics Magazine|volume=No. 07|page=50|via=|author2=Turner, Tracy|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref>  or other travelers while also reducing the number of signs needed.  Doggett's system eliminated two-thirds of the highway signs that had originally been proposed for the Tampa airport.<ref name=\"New York Times Magazine\"/>\n* Building the verbal or symbolic message into the architecture rather than tacking it on as a sign.\n* Creating a visual symbol to brand the airport and represent it as a gateway to the surrounding region.<ref name=\"Experiential Graphics Magazine\" />\n\nOther notable graphics and design projects that she has worked on include [[Madison Square Garden]], the [[Philadelphia]] subway system,<ref name=\"New York Times Magazine\"/> the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], [[Niagara Falls]] International Convention Center, [[Jones Hall for the Performing Arts]] in [[Houston]], and Fairfax Hospital in Virginia.  Doggett\u2019s designs have been awarded the [[American Institute of Architects]]\u2019 National Award of Merit, the Progressive Architecture Design Award,<ref name=\"Tulane Newcomb Alumnae\" />  American Iron and Steel Institute's Design in Steel Citation, and two Design Awards co-sponsored by the [[U.S. Department of Transportation]] and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]].{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nIn her fine art work since 2007, Doggett has developed the concept of the Iconochrome,  which she has described as \u201cgeometric designs in colors expressing philosophically profound messages.\u201d<ref name=\"Yale\" /> She has also described an Iconochrome as a colorful image or \u201cIcon, an image with meaning, plus chrome, color.\u201d<ref name=\"The Tennessean\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=MiChelle|title=Artist Interprets Proverbs through Talking Graphics|newspaper=The Tennessean (Sunday Arts and Entertainment section, Nashville, TN)|date=Oct 4, 2009}}</ref> Her work has been exhibited at the [[Yale University Art Gallery]].;<ref name=\"Yale\" /><ref name=\"Art Daily 1\">{{cite web|title=Special Installation Showcases Unique \"Visual Language\" Depicting Timeless Philosophical Messages|url=http://artdaily.com/news/35777/Special-Installation-Showcases-Unique--Visual-Language--Depicting-Timeless-Philosophical-Messages#.Uxla017WSXU.|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2010/01/26/yuag-features-signs-as-art |title=YUAG features signs as art |publisher=Yale Daily News |date=2010-01-26 |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref> [[Tennessee State Museum]], Nashville; Armory Art Center, West Palm Beach, FL; Tampa International Airport; Lighthouse Art Center, Tequesta, FL; Northern Trust, North Palm Beach, FL; Maritime and Classic Boat Museum, Jensen Beach, FL; Chapter Two, Corea, ME; [[College of the Atlantic]], Bar Harbor, ME;<ref name=\"College of the Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=http://news.coa.edu/2012/07/01/doggetts-bold-graphics/|title=Doggett's Bold Graphics|last=Gold|first=Donna|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> Littlefield Gallery, Winter Harbor, ME;<ref name=\"Ellsworth American\" /> [[Elliott Museum]], Stuart, FL.<ref name=\"Art Daily 2\">{{cite web|title=Josef Albers and Heirs exhibit on view at The Elliott Museum in Florida|url=http://artdaily.com/news/67080/Josef-Albers-and-Heirs-exhibit-on-view-at-The-Elliot-Museum-in-Florida#.UxlYk17WSXU|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://martincountytimes.com/elliott-museum-presents-albers-heirs-josef-albers-neil-welliver-and-jane-davis-doggett |title=Elliott Museum presents 'Albers & Heirs: Josef Albers, Neil Welliver, and Jane Davis Doggett' |work=Martin County Times |publisher=Martincountytimes.com |date=2013-11-09 |accessdate=2014-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"250\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:2018 Jane Davis Doggett Wayfinder Designs, Tampa Airport Exhibition.jpg|''Coding by Color, Letter, and Symbol,'' Jane Davis Doggett, ca. 1962.</br>Tampa Bay Airport Exhibition, 2014<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=Coding by Color, Letter, and Symbol |url=https://i.imgur.com/2cFQy6K.jpg |publisher=Tampa Bay Airport}}</ref>\nFile:1960 Jane Davis Doggett Terminal Design.jpg|Baltimore-Washington International Airport, Jane Davis Doggett, ca. 1960.</br? Doggett used airport logos as unifying graphic elements.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=Baltimore-Washington International Terminal Design |url=https://segd.org/sites/default/files/styles/galleryformatter_slide/public/30210001_0.jpg?itok=payOHTCm |publisher=Society for Experiential Graphic Design |date=2014}}</ref>\nFile:2012 Jane Davis Doggett, Knockabouts off Dixon Point.jpg|''Knockabouts off Dixon Point,'' Jane Davis Doggett, 2012.<br/>Later graphic work<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=Knockabouts off Dixon Point |url=https://www.ellsworthamerican.com/living/arts-a-living/doggett-offers-graphics-that-grab-the-eye-at-blum/ |publisher=Ellsworth American |date=2012}}</ref>\nFile:2007 Twenty-Third Psalm For The Twenty-First Century, sculpture by Jane Davis Doggett.jpg|''The Twenty-Third Psalm,'' Jane Davis Doggett, 2012. Final Panel: \"And I will dwell in the house of the Lord forever.\"<br/>Saint Thomas More Chapel & Center, Yale University, New HaveN, CT<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doggett |first1=Jane Davis |title=The Twenty-Third Psalm |url=https://stm.yale.edu/23rd-psalm |publisher=Yale University |location=New Haven, CT |date=2012}}</ref> \n</gallery>\n\n==Awards & Honors==\n:2016: inducted into the [[Florida Artists Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dos.myflorida.com/cultural/programs/florida-artists-hall-of-fame/|title=Florida Artists Hall of Fame - Division of Cultural Affairs - Florida Department of State|website=dos.myflorida.com|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n:2018: Society for Experiential Graphic Design Fellow<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 SEGD Fellow: Jane David Doggett |url=https://segd.org/jane-davis-doggett |publisher=SEGD |location=Washington, DC |date=2018}}</ref>\n\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doggett, Jane Davis}}\n[[Category:Yale School of Art alumni]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLa(link changed toLouisiana) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jane_Davis_Doggett"}
{"title_page": "Mazar-e-Quaid", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Mazar-e-Quaid\n| native_name = {{Nastaliq|\u0645\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0642\u0627\u0626\u062f}}\n| image = Jinnah Mausoleum.JPG\n| caption = The mausoleum is the resting place of the [[Pakistan|Pakistan's]] founder [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]\n| architect = [[Yahya Merchant|Yahya C. Merchant]]\n| floor_area = {{convert|3100|m2}}\n| coordinates = {{coord|24.875354|N|67.040835|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| opened_date = \n| location = [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]\n| architectural = \n| architectural_style = [[Modern architecture|Modernist]]\n| height = {{convert|43|m}}\n| building_type = [[Mausoleum]]\n| client = [[Government of Pakistan]]\n| start_date = 31 July 1960\n| inauguration_date = 18 January 1971\n}}{{Muhammad Ali Jinnah sidebar}}\n'''Mazar-e-Quaid''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0645\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0642\u0627\u0626\u062f}}}}), also known as '''Jinnah Mausoleum''' or the '''National Mausoleum''', is the final resting place of ''Quaid-e-Azam'' (\"Great Leader\") [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]], the founder of [[Pakistan]]. Designed in a 1960s [[Modern architecture|modernist style]], it was completed in 1971, and is an iconic symbol of [[Karachi]] as well as one of the most popular tourist sites in the city.<ref>http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206035635/http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html|date=2016-12-06}}, Mazar-e-Quaid on Pakistan Tourism Development Corporation website, Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref> The mausoleum complex also contains the tomb of Jinnah's sister, ''M\u0101der-e Millat'' (\"Mother of the Nation\") [[Fatima Jinnah]], as well as those of [[Liaquat Ali Khan]] and [[Nurul Amin]], the first and eighth [[Prime Ministers of Pakistan]] respectively. \nThe tomb of [[Sardar Abdur Rab Nishtar]], a stalwart of the [[Muslim League (Opposition)|Muslim League]] from [[Peshawar]], is also located there. \n\n==Location==\nThe mausoleum is located in a prominent and highly visible location in the [[Jamshed Quarters]] locality of central [[Karachi]] - along the northern edge of the colonial-era core at the end of [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah Road]]. The mausoleum is surrounded by large garden laid out in a neo-Mughal style in the dense central city, with large traffic rotaries at 3 of its 4 corners.\n\n== History ==\n[[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]'s corporal death occurred in 1948, and his final resting place was marked by a large white marble slab that was raised on a plinth accessed by marble steps.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Manekshah|first=Farida J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NBkvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT63&dq=Quaid-e-Azam+Tomb&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx3rqJ8t7oAhW3CjQIHdoCD5AQ6AEwBnoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=Quaid-e-Azam%20Tomb&f=false|title=Memory of Beheram|date=2016-12-01|publisher=eBook Versions|isbn=978-1-84396-433-9|language=en}}</ref> In 1949, the Quaid-e-Azam Memorial Fund (QMF) was established, which received numerous suggestions for the establishment of a memorial in Jinnah's honor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/4434976.pdf|title=MONUMENT WITHOUT QUALITIES|last=Yusuf|first=Shundana|date=|year=June 2001|website=|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> By 1952, his mausoleum was capped by a small dome, with a cabinet that contained some of his personal effects along a wall near his grave.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tanqeed.org/2016/05/making-karachi/#identifier_0_12266|title=Making Karachi|last=Rajani|first=Shahana|last2=Rajani|first2=Shayan|date=May 2016|website=www.tanqeed.org|publisher=Tanqeed|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The site had an air of neglect which angered many.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Fatima Jinnah]] and the QMF received numerous letters from concerned Pakistanis at the sad state of his tomb, and advocated for a more befitting monument to Jinnah.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn 1952, the QMF proposed to erect 4 monuments across Pakistan to Jinnah's memory - a mausoleum and mosque on the current site in central Karachi, a [[Darul uloom|''Dar-ul-Uloom'']] religions school in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], and a University of Science and Technology in [[East Pakistan]].<ref>S. R Ghauri: \"Humble Symbol of Gratitude\", Editor Altaf Hussain, The Daily Dawn, Karachi: 12 Sept. 1962.</ref> In 1954, an Indian architect was selected to design the mausoleum, but was later dismissed.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1955, a Turkish architect was hired, but his plan was rejected as well.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1957, the  [[Government of Pakistan]] held an international competition to design a new mausoleum for Jinnah.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Herrle|first=Peter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vs0Us4SSxUoC&pg=PA129&dq=Quaid-e-Azam+Tomb&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx3rqJ8t7oAhW3CjQIHdoCD5AQ6AEwBXoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=Quaid-e-Azam%20Tomb&f=false|title=Architecture and Identity|last2=Wegerhoff|first2=Erik|date=2008|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=978-3-8258-1088-7|language=en}}</ref> The competition was initially won by British architect [[William Whitfield (architect)|William Whitfield]],<ref>Zahir-ud Deen Khwaja: Memoirs of an Architect. Lahore: Printhouse, 1998, p. 63.</ref> of the [[Raglan Squire|Raglan Squire and Partners]] firm. The state's efforts to select a design were paralleled by the efforts of the Jinnah's sister, [[Fatima Jinnah]], who sought input from the public in the design of a monument to her brother.<ref name=\":2\" /> Fatima Jinnah effectively vetoed the 1957 proposal, and assumed control of the QMF. She then commissioned architect [[Yahya Merchant]],<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|last=Martyris|first=Nina|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-06-17/india/27848575_1_jinnah-mausoleum-mohammad-ali-jinnah-tomb|title=A Jinnah mausoleum in Mumbai?|date=17 June 2005|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> a [[Bombay]] based architect who was a personal friend of Jinnah,<ref name=\":0\" /> to design the monument.\n\n[[President Ayub Khan]] laid the foundation stone for the monument on July 31, 1960. It was inaugurated by [[Yahya Khan]] on 18 January 1971.<ref name=\":1\" /> The gardens surrounding the mausoleum were not completed until December 24, 2000.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Proposed designs ==\nNumerous proposals were submitted by Pakistani citizens following independence - ranging from a shrine, to a neo-Mughal monument.<ref name=\":1\" /> The idealists suggestions directly from ordinary Pakistani citizens reflected the \"radical utopianism\" that swept through the Muslims of the subcontinent around the [[Pakistan Movement]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1954, an Indian architect was selected to design the mausoleum, but his design could not gain consensus among members of the QMF, and so was dismissed.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1955, a Turkish architect was hired, but his plan was rejected as being \"too elaborate,\" and \"almost despotic.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The QMF's mandate stalled as consensus over the design was lacking.<ref name=\":1\" /> Proposals from the Malay engineer and architect [[Ainuddin Wahid|Ainuddin,]] suggested a complex reminiscent of a Sufi shrine,<ref name=\":2\" /> with mosques, libraries, school, restaurants, and shops to merge into the fabric of the city.<ref>''Letter from Ainuddin to Fatima Jinnah,'' undated, National Archives, Islamabad, Fatima Jinnah Papers, Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum, Serial no. 518/ 1949-65/85, pp. 56-67. and ''Letter from Ainuddin to Fatima Jinnah'', 4 October 1959, National Archives, Islamabad, Fatima Jinnah Papers, Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum, Serial no. 518/ 1949-65/85, p. 28.</ref> \n\n1957, the  [[Government of Pakistan]] held an international competition to design a new mausoleum for Jinnah.<ref name=\":2\" /> 6 of the 8 jurists were European modernist architects.<ref name=\":1\" /> The 1957 competition was won by [[William Whitfield (architect)|William Whitfield]] of the modernist [[Raglan Squire|Reglan Squire and Partners]] firm. [https://www.tanqeed.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/photo4.png The plan called for an avante garde neo-futurist mausoleum] mounted on an elevated platform in a neo-Mughal garden, with a central parabola and pointed edges at its six corners reaching out \"in an exuberant motion towards the sky.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Following the 1958 coup of [[President Ayub Khan]], who presented himself as a moderniser, the Whitfield-Squire proposal gained favor among the military elite, although public reception was not warm.<ref name=\":1\" /> Fatima Jinnah opposed Whitfield's plan on several fronts, including its design, its selection by an international rather than Pakistani jury, and the fact that it was awarded to a British national,<ref name=\":0\" /> which challenged the desire of Pakistanis for a de-colonial future.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFatima Jinnah then assumed control the the design process, and chose the proposals of architect [[Yahya Merchant]],<ref name=\":3\" /> a [[Bombay]] based architect who was a personal friend of Jinnah.<ref name=\":0\" /> Merchant\u2019s design was of a cuboid structure with a dome, clad in white marble. The monument was placed on an elevated platform, set in a 61-acre gardened hill looking over the city. The new design was praised by eminent professor [[Ahmad Hasan Dani]] as \u201cnot a slavish imitation of the old tradition. Actually it partakes of the Muslim spirit of the past but it is created to meet the new demand of the present in the technique of the present day.\u201d<ref>Ahmad Hasan Dani, introduction to ''The Quaid-i-Azam Mausoleum in Pictures'', ed. Afsar Akhtar Husain and Dani (Islamabad: National Book Foundation, 1976)</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Samanid Shrine.jpg|thumb|left|The design of the Mazar-e-Quaid was influenced by the [[Samanid Mausoleum]] in [[Bukhara]], [[Uzbekistan]], built between 892 and 943 CE.]]\nThe mausoleum was designed in the [[Modern architecture|modernist style]] popular during the 1960s and 1970s, and has been termed a \"traditional monument of a modernist period.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> It appears simple at a distance, but \"exuberant in its use of material and complex in its detailing when viewed\" closely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The use of white marble to suggest purity, and pure geometric forms, are designed to portray Jinnah as a larger-than-life figure.<ref name=\":0\" /> The location and style of the monument both serve to inspire passersby.<ref>Ahmed Hasan Dani, ''The Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum in Pictures''. Islamabad: Ministry of Education Press, 1976</ref>\n\nIt is clad in white marble, and has curved arches and copper grills set on an elevated 54-square-meter platform.<ref>http://www.cybercity-online.net/Pakistan/html/shrines_tombs___mosques_in_pak.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111191601/http://www.cybercity-online.net/Pakistan/html/shrines_tombs___mosques_in_pak.html |date=2019-11-11 }} Shrines & Tombs in Pakistan, Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref>  The cool inner sanctum reflects the green of a four-tiered crystal chandelier gifted by the [[People's Republic of China]].<ref>http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206035635/http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html|date=2016-12-06}}, Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn the interior of the grave complex, there are four graves in a row and one to the north. The one to the north, which is decorated with a series of black floral design at the base, belongs to Miss [Fatima Jinnah], Quaid-e-Azam's sister. Out of the four graves in a row, first extreme two belong to [[Liaquat Ali Khan]], the first Prime Minister of Pakistan and [[Begum]] [[Ra'ana Liaquat Ali Khan]] lying side by side. The other extreme grave belongs to Sardar [[Abdur Rab Nishtar]]. In the middle lies buried [[Nurul Amin]], who was the eighth Prime Minister of Pakistan. All these graves are made of Italian white marble, and they are of the box type, like the sarcophagus of Jinnah, placed on a triple base. But the sides of these graves are tapering inward while that of Jinnah are diverging outward. These are all plain graves, except that of Mohtarma Fatima Jinnah, which has a basal floral ornamentation.\n\nThe mausoleum is located in a 53-hectare park and the building has a footprint of {{convert|75|by|75|m|abbr=on}} with a height of {{convert|43|m|abbr=on}}, built on a {{convert|4|m|abbr=on}} high platform. In each wall is placed an entrance. Fifteen successive fountains lead to the platform from one side and from all sides terraced avenues lead to the gates. Around the mausoleum is a park fitted with strong beamed spot-lights which at night project light on the white mausoleum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.com.pk/|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915143637/http://www.heritage.com.pk/|archivedate=15 September 2010|accessdate=2010-09-27}}, Retrieve 8 April 2016 </ref>\n<ref name=\"3d\">https://web.archive.org/web/20170821175749/http://www.3dillumination.com/blog/2017/08/16/14th-august-70th-independence-day-mazar-e-quaid-gift-nation/</ref>\n\n==Significance==\nOfficial and military ceremonies take place here on special occasions, such as on 23 March (Pakistan Day), 14 August (Independence Day), 11 September (the anniversary of Jinnah's death) and 25 December (Jinnah's birthday). Dignitaries and officials from foreign countries also visit the mausoleum during official tours. On 14 August 2017, [[Independence Day (Pakistan)| Pakistan's Independence Day]], it was used for paying a tribute to Jinnah through 3d projection mapping show by 3D illumination.<ref name=\"3d\"/>\n\n<br />\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Aerial view of Quid e Azam's tomb in Karachi.JPG|Aerial view of the building\nFile:Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum-18.jpg| The tomb is illuminated at night \nFile:Quaid Mazar 5.jpg|View of the chandelier donated by an Islamic association in China\nFile:Mausoleum of the quaid e azam muhammad ali jinnah farrah 1.jpg\nFile:Qaid-e-Azam tomb, Marar-e-Qaid 09.jpg\nFile:Qaid-e-Azam tomb, Marar-e-Qaid 40.jpg\nFile:Tomb Detail.jpg|Inscriptions on the cenotaph, in [[Urdu]] and [[Bengali language|Bengali.]]\nFile:Celebrating Pakistan Day; Remembering the Founder (8582495894).jpg|A view of the cenotaph\nFile:MazareQuaid.jpg\nFile:Mazaar-e-Quaid.jpg\nFile:Mazar View at night.JPG|Evening view\nFile:Qaid-e-Azam tomb, Marar-e-Qaid 18.jpg|View from the gardens which surround the mausoleum\n</gallery>{{Gallery|title=}}\n\n==See also==\n*[https://www.tanqeed.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/photo4.png Image of Reglan Squire's proposal for Jinnah Mausoleum]\n*[[Wazir Mansion]], Jinnah's birthplace in Karachi\n* [[Governor's House (Karachi)|Governor-General's House]], Jinnah's official residence in Karachi\n* [[Quaid-e-Azam Residency]], Jinnah's residence in Balochistan where he spent the last days of his life\n* [[Jinnah House]], Muhammad Ali Jinnah's house in Mumbai, India\n* [[Quaid-e-Azam House]], Muhammad Ali Jinnah's House in Karachi\n* [[Quaid-e-Azam House|Flagstaff House]], Muhammad Ali Jinnah's House in Karachi\n\n== References ==\n<br />\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Mazar-e-Quaid}}\n\n{{National symbols of Pakistan}}\n{{Jinnah}}\n{{Cultural heritage sites in Sindh |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Karachi topics}}\n\n[[Category:National symbols of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Sindh]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Karachi]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Karachi]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1970]]\n[[Category:Karachi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Mazar-e-Quaid\n| native_name = {{Nastaliq|\u0645\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0642\u0627\u0626\u062f}}\n| image = Jinnah Mausoleum.JPG\n| caption = The mausoleum is the resting place of the [[Pakistan|Pakistan's]] founder [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]\n| architect = [[Yahya Merchant|Yahya C. Merchant]]\n| floor_area = {{convert|3100|m2}}\n| coordinates = {{coord|24.875354|N|67.040835|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| opened_date = \n| location = [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]\n| architectural = \n| architectural_style = [[Modern architecture|Modernist]]\n| height = {{convert|43|m}}\n| building_type = [[Mausoleum]]\n| client = [[Government of Pakistan]]\n| start_date = 31 July 1960\n| inauguration_date = 18 January 1971\n}}{{Muhammad Ali Jinnah sidebar}}\n'''Mazar-e-Quaid''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0645\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0642\u0627\u0626\u062f}}}}), also known as '''Jinnah Mausoleum''' or the '''National Mausoleum''', is the final resting place of ''Quaid-e-Azam'' (\"Great Leader\") [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]], the founder of [[Pakistan]]. Designed in a 1960s [[Modern architecture|modernist style]], it was completed in 1971, and is an iconic symbol of [[Karachi]] as well as one of the most popular tourist sites in the city.<ref>http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206035635/http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html|date=2016-12-06}}, Mazar-e-Quaid on Pakistan Tourism Development Corporation website, Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref> The mausoleum complex also contains the tomb of Jinnah's sister, ''M\u0101der-e Millat'' (\"Mother of the Nation\") [[Fatima Jinnah]], as well as those of [[Liaquat Ali Khan]] and [[Nurul Amin]], the first and eighth [[Prime Ministers of Pakistan]] respectively. \nThe tomb of [[Sardar Abdur Rab Nishtar]], a stalwart of the [[Muslim League (Opposition)|Muslim League]] from [[Peshawar]], is also located there. \n\n==Location==\nThe mausoleum is located in a prominent and highly visible location in the [[Jamshed Quarters]] locality of central [[Karachi]] - along the northern edge of the colonial-era core at the end of [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah Road]]. The mausoleum is surrounded by large garden laid out in a neo-Mughal style in the dense central city, with large traffic rotaries at 3 of its 4 corners.\n\n== History ==\n[[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]'s corporal death occurred in 1948, and his final resting place was marked by a large white marble slab that was raised on a plinth accessed by marble steps.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Manekshah|first=Farida J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NBkvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT63&dq=Quaid-e-Azam+Tomb&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx3rqJ8t7oAhW3CjQIHdoCD5AQ6AEwBnoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=Quaid-e-Azam%20Tomb&f=false|title=Memory of Beheram|date=2016-12-01|publisher=eBook Versions|isbn=978-1-84396-433-9|language=en}}</ref> In 1949, the the Quaid-e-Azam Memorial Fund (QMF) was established, which received numerous suggestions for the establishment of a memorial in Jinnah's honor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/4434976.pdf|title=MONUMENT WITHOUT QUALITIES|last=Yusuf|first=Shundana|date=|year=June 2001|website=|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> By 1952, his mausoleum was capped by a small dome, with a cabinet that contained some of his personal effects along a wall near his grave.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tanqeed.org/2016/05/making-karachi/#identifier_0_12266|title=Making Karachi|last=Rajani|first=Shahana|last2=Rajani|first2=Shayan|date=May 2016|website=www.tanqeed.org|publisher=Tanqeed|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The site had an air of neglect which angered many.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Fatima Jinnah]] and the QMF received numerous letters from concerned Pakistanis at the sad state of his tomb, and advocated for a more befitting monument to Jinnah.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn 1952, the QMF proposed to erect 4 monuments across Pakistan to Jinnah's memory - a mausoleum and mosque on the current site in central Karachi, a [[Darul uloom|''Dar-ul-Uloom'']] religions school in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], and a University of Science and Technology in [[East Pakistan]].<ref>S. R Ghauri: \"Humble Symbol of Gratitude\", Editor Altaf Hussain, The Daily Dawn, Karachi: 12 Sept. 1962.</ref> In 1954, an Indian architect was selected to design the mausoleum, but was later dismissed.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1955, a Turkish architect was hired, but his plan was rejected as well.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1957, the  [[Government of Pakistan]] held an international competition to design a new mausoleum for Jinnah.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Herrle|first=Peter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vs0Us4SSxUoC&pg=PA129&dq=Quaid-e-Azam+Tomb&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx3rqJ8t7oAhW3CjQIHdoCD5AQ6AEwBXoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=Quaid-e-Azam%20Tomb&f=false|title=Architecture and Identity|last2=Wegerhoff|first2=Erik|date=2008|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=978-3-8258-1088-7|language=en}}</ref> The competition was initially won by British architect [[William Whitfield (architect)|William Whitfield]],<ref>Zahir-ud Deen Khwaja: Memoirs of an Architect. Lahore: Printhouse, 1998, p. 63.</ref> of the [[Raglan Squire|Raglan Squire and Partners]] firm. The state's efforts to select a design were paralleled by the efforts of the Jinnah's sister, [[Fatima Jinnah]], who sought input from the public in the design of a monument to her brother.<ref name=\":2\" /> Fatima Jinnah effectively vetoed the 1957 proposal, and assumed control of the QMF. She then commissioned architect [[Yahya Merchant]],<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|last=Martyris|first=Nina|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-06-17/india/27848575_1_jinnah-mausoleum-mohammad-ali-jinnah-tomb|title=A Jinnah mausoleum in Mumbai?|date=17 June 2005|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> a [[Bombay]] based architect who was a personal friend of Jinnah,<ref name=\":0\" /> to design the monument.\n\n[[President Ayub Khan]] laid the foundation stone for the monument on July 31, 1960. It was inaugurated by [[Yahya Khan]] on 18 January 1971.<ref name=\":1\" /> The gardens surrounding the mausoleum were not completed until December 24, 2000.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Proposed designs ==\nNumerous proposals were submitted by Pakistani citizens following independence - ranging from a shrine, to a neo-Mughal monument.<ref name=\":1\" /> The idealists suggestions directly from ordinary Pakistani citizens reflected the \"radical utopianism\" that swept through the Muslims of the subcontinent around the [[Pakistan Movement]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1954, an Indian architect was selected to design the mausoleum, but his design could not gain consensus among members of the QMF, and so was dismissed.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1955, a Turkish architect was hired, but his plan was rejected as being \"too elaborate,\" and \"almost despotic.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The QMF's mandate stalled as consensus over the design was lacking.<ref name=\":1\" /> Proposals from the Malay engineer and architect [[Ainuddin Wahid|Ainuddin,]] suggested a complex reminiscent of a Sufi shrine,<ref name=\":2\" /> with mosques, libraries, school, restaurants, and shops to merge into the fabric of the city.<ref>''Letter from Ainuddin to Fatima Jinnah,'' undated, National Archives, Islamabad, Fatima Jinnah Papers, Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum, Serial no. 518/ 1949-65/85, pp. 56-67. and ''Letter from Ainuddin to Fatima Jinnah'', 4 October 1959, National Archives, Islamabad, Fatima Jinnah Papers, Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum, Serial no. 518/ 1949-65/85, p. 28.</ref> \n\n1957, the  [[Government of Pakistan]] held an international competition to design a new mausoleum for Jinnah.<ref name=\":2\" /> 6 of the 8 jurists were European modernist architects.<ref name=\":1\" /> The 1957 competition was won by [[William Whitfield (architect)|William Whitfield]] of the modernist [[Raglan Squire|Reglan Squire and Partners]] firm. [https://www.tanqeed.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/photo4.png The plan called for an avante garde neo-futurist mausoleum] mounted on an elevated platform in a neo-Mughal garden, with a central parabola and pointed edges at its six corners reaching out \"in an exuberant motion towards the sky.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Following the 1958 coup of [[President Ayub Khan]], who presented himself as a moderniser, the Whitfield-Squire proposal gained favor among the military elite, although public reception was not warm.<ref name=\":1\" /> Fatima Jinnah opposed Whitfield's plan on several fronts, including its design, its selection by an international rather than Pakistani jury, and the fact that it was awarded to a British national,<ref name=\":0\" /> which challenged the desire of Pakistanis for a de-colonial future.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFatima Jinnah then assumed control the the design process, and chose the proposals of architect [[Yahya Merchant]],<ref name=\":3\" /> a [[Bombay]] based architect who was a personal friend of Jinnah.<ref name=\":0\" /> Merchant\u2019s design was of a cuboid structure with a dome, clad in white marble. The monument was placed on an elevated platform, set in a 61-acre gardened hill looking over the city. The new design was praised by eminent professor [[Ahmad Hasan Dani]] as \u201cnot a slavish imitation of the old tradition. Actually it partakes of the Muslim spirit of the past but it is created to meet the new demand of the present in the technique of the present day.\u201d<ref>Ahmad Hasan Dani, introduction to ''The Quaid-i-Azam Mausoleum in Pictures'', ed. Afsar Akhtar Husain and Dani (Islamabad: National Book Foundation, 1976)</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Samanid Shrine.jpg|thumb|left|The design of the Mazar-e-Quaid was influenced by the [[Samanid Mausoleum]] in [[Bukhara]], [[Uzbekistan]], built between 892 and 943 CE.]]\nThe mausoleum was designed in the [[Modern architecture|modernist style]] popular during the 1960s and 1970s, and has been termed a \"traditional monument of a modernist period.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> It appears simple at a distance, but \"exuberant in its use of material and complex in its detailing when viewed\" closely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The use of white marble to suggest purity, and pure geometric forms, are designed to portray Jinnah as a larger-than-life figure.<ref name=\":0\" /> The location and style of the monument both serve to inspire passersby.<ref>Ahmed Hasan Dani, ''The Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum in Pictures''. Islamabad: Ministry of Education Press, 1976</ref>\n\nIt is clad in white marble, and has curved arches and copper grills set on an elevated 54-square-meter platform.<ref>http://www.cybercity-online.net/Pakistan/html/shrines_tombs___mosques_in_pak.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111191601/http://www.cybercity-online.net/Pakistan/html/shrines_tombs___mosques_in_pak.html |date=2019-11-11 }} Shrines & Tombs in Pakistan, Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref>  The cool inner sanctum reflects the green of a four-tiered crystal chandelier gifted by the [[People's Republic of China]].<ref>http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206035635/http://www.tourism.gov.pk/karachi_sindh.html|date=2016-12-06}}, Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn the interior of the grave complex, there are four graves in a row and one to the north. The one to the north, which is decorated with a series of black floral design at the base, belongs to Miss [Fatima Jinnah], Quaid-e-Azam's sister. Out of the four graves in a row, first extreme two belong to [[Liaquat Ali Khan]], the first Prime Minister of Pakistan and [[Begum]] [[Ra'ana Liaquat Ali Khan]] lying side by side. The other extreme grave belongs to Sardar [[Abdur Rab Nishtar]]. In the middle lies buried [[Nurul Amin]], who was the eighth Prime Minister of Pakistan. All these graves are made of Italian white marble, and they are of the box type, like the sarcophagus of Jinnah, placed on a triple base. But the sides of these graves are tapering inward while that of Jinnah are diverging outward. These are all plain graves, except that of Mohtarma Fatima Jinnah, which has a basal floral ornamentation.\n\nThe mausoleum is located in a 53-hectare park and the building has a footprint of {{convert|75|by|75|m|abbr=on}} with a height of {{convert|43|m|abbr=on}}, built on a {{convert|4|m|abbr=on}} high platform. In each wall is placed an entrance. Fifteen successive fountains lead to the platform from one side and from all sides terraced avenues lead to the gates. Around the mausoleum is a park fitted with strong beamed spot-lights which at night project light on the white mausoleum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.com.pk/|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915143637/http://www.heritage.com.pk/|archivedate=15 September 2010|accessdate=2010-09-27}}, Retrieve 8 April 2016 </ref>\n<ref name=\"3d\">https://web.archive.org/web/20170821175749/http://www.3dillumination.com/blog/2017/08/16/14th-august-70th-independence-day-mazar-e-quaid-gift-nation/</ref>\n\n==Significance==\nOfficial and military ceremonies take place here on special occasions, such as on 23 March (Pakistan Day), 14 August (Independence Day), 11 September (the anniversary of Jinnah's death) and 25 December (Jinnah's birthday). Dignitaries and officials from foreign countries also visit the mausoleum during official tours. On 14 August 2017, [[Independence Day (Pakistan)| Pakistan's Independence Day]], it was used for paying a tribute to Jinnah through 3d projection mapping show by 3D illumination.<ref name=\"3d\"/>\n\n<br />\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Aerial view of Quid e Azam's tomb in Karachi.JPG|Aerial view of the building\nFile:Quaid-e-Azam Mausoleum-18.jpg| The tomb is illuminated at night \nFile:Quaid Mazar 5.jpg|View of the chandelier donated by an Islamic association in China\nFile:Mausoleum of the quaid e azam muhammad ali jinnah farrah 1.jpg\nFile:Qaid-e-Azam tomb, Marar-e-Qaid 09.jpg\nFile:Qaid-e-Azam tomb, Marar-e-Qaid 40.jpg\nFile:Tomb Detail.jpg|Inscriptions on the cenotaph, in [[Urdu]] and [[Bengali language|Bengali.]]\nFile:Celebrating Pakistan Day; Remembering the Founder (8582495894).jpg|A view of the cenotaph\nFile:MazareQuaid.jpg\nFile:Mazaar-e-Quaid.jpg\nFile:Mazar View at night.JPG|Evening view\nFile:Qaid-e-Azam tomb, Marar-e-Qaid 18.jpg|View from the gardens which surround the mausoleum\n</gallery>{{Gallery|title=}}\n\n==See also==\n*[https://www.tanqeed.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/photo4.png Image of Reglan Squire's proposal for Jinnah Mausoleum]\n*[[Wazir Mansion]], Jinnah's birthplace in Karachi\n* [[Governor's House (Karachi)|Governor-General's House]], Jinnah's official residence in Karachi\n* [[Quaid-e-Azam Residency]], Jinnah's residence in Balochistan where he spent the last days of his life\n* [[Jinnah House]], Muhammad Ali Jinnah's house in Mumbai, India\n* [[Quaid-e-Azam House]], Muhammad Ali Jinnah's House in Karachi\n* [[Quaid-e-Azam House|Flagstaff House]], Muhammad Ali Jinnah's House in Karachi\n\n== References ==\n<br />\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Mazar-e-Quaid}}\n\n{{National symbols of Pakistan}}\n{{Jinnah}}\n{{Cultural heritage sites in Sindh |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Karachi topics}}\n\n[[Category:National symbols of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Sindh]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Karachi]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Karachi]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1970]]\n[[Category:Karachi]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mazar-e-Quaid"}
{"title_page": "2009 NBA Finals", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2010}}\n{{NBA Finals summary\n| image = 2009 NBA Finals.png\n| league = NBA\n| year = 2009\n| runnerup = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| runnerup_coach = [[Stan Van Gundy]]\n| runnerup_games = 1\n| champion = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| champion_coach = [[Phil Jackson]]\n| champion_games = 4\n| date = June 4\u201314\n| MVP = [[Kobe Bryant]]<br>(Los Angeles Lakers)\n| television = [[NBA on ABC|ABC]] (U.S.)<br> [[The Sports Network|TSN]] (Canada)\n| announcers = [[Mike Breen]], [[Jeff Van Gundy]] and [[Mark Jackson (basketball)|Mark Jackson]]\n| HOFers = '''Lakers:'''<br>Kobe Bryant (2020)<br>'''Coaches:'''<br>Phil Jackson (2007)\n| radio_network = [[NBA on ESPN Radio|ESPN]]\n| radio_announcers = [[Mike Tirico]], [[Hubie Brown]] and [[Jack Ramsay]]\n| referees_1 = [[Dan Crawford (basketball referee)|Dan Crawford]], [[Joe DeRosa (referee)|Joe DeRosa]], [[Ken Mauer]]\n| referees_2 = [[Steve Javie]], [[Monty McCutchen]], Tom Washington\n| referees_3 = [[Joe Crawford (basketball, born 1951)|Joe Crawford]], Derrick Stafford, Mark Wunderlich\n| referees_4 = [[Bennett Salvatore]], Mike Callahan, Scott Foster\n| referees_5 = [[Dan Crawford (basketball referee)|Dan Crawford]], [[Joe DeRosa (referee)|Joe DeRosa]], [[Ken Mauer]]\n| ECF result = [[2008\u201309 Orlando Magic season|Magic]] defeated [[2008\u201309 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cavaliers]], 4\u20132\n| WCF result = [[2008\u201309 Los Angeles Lakers season|Lakers]] defeated [[2008\u201309 Denver Nuggets season|Nuggets]], 4\u20132\n}}\n\nThe '''2009 NBA Finals''' was the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA)'s championship series for the [[2008\u201309 NBA season|2008\u201309 season]]. The [[best-of-seven playoff]] was contested between the [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] champion [[2008\u201309 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]] (who were also the [[2007\u201308 Los Angeles Lakers season|defending Western Conference champions]]), and the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] champion [[2008\u201309 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/playoffs/2009-nba-finals-magic-vs-lakers.html|title=2009 NBA Finals - Orlando Magic vs. Los Angeles Lakers|website=Basketball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> The Lakers defeated the Magic, four games to one, to win the franchise's 15th NBA championship. The 63rd edition of the [[NBA Finals|championship series]] was played between June 4 and June 14 and was broadcast on U.S. television on [[NBA on ABC|ABC]].\n\nThe Lakers earned their berth into the [[2009 NBA Playoffs|playoffs]] by winning the [[Pacific Division (NBA)|Pacific Division]]. The Magic won the [[Southeast Division (NBA)|Southeast Division]] to earn their berth. The Lakers reached the NBA Finals by defeating the [[Utah Jazz]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 NBA Playoffs#.281.29 Los Angeles Lakers vs. .288.29 Utah Jazz|Western Conference First Round]], the [[Houston Rockets]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 NBA Playoffs#.281.29 Los Angeles Lakers vs. .285.29 Houston Rockets|Western Conference Semifinals]], and the [[Denver Nuggets]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 NBA Playoffs#Conference Finals: .281.29 Los Angeles Lakers vs. .282.29 Denver Nuggets|Western Conference Finals]]. The Magic reached the NBA Finals by defeating the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 NBA Playoffs#.283.29 Orlando Magic vs. .286.29 Philadelphia 76ers|Eastern Conference First Round]], the [[2007-08 Boston Celtics season|defending champion]] [[Boston Celtics]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 NBA Playoffs#.282.29 Boston Celtics vs. .283.29 Orlando Magic|Eastern Conference Semifinals]], and the league best [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in the best-of-seven [[2009 NBA Playoffs#Conference Finals: .281.29 Cleveland Cavaliers vs. .283.29 Orlando Magic|Eastern Conference Finals]]. The NBA Finals were staged under a 2\u20133\u20132 rotation, with the Lakers holding [[home advantage|home-court advantage]] as they had a better regular season record than the Magic.\n\n[[Kobe Bryant]] led the team to a Game 1 win with 40 points, eight rebounds, and eight assists. Game 2 was a high-scoring affair that the Lakers ultimately won on both strong defensive play and last minute heroics by Bryant, [[Derek Fisher]], and [[Pau Gasol]] during the overtime. A record-breaking performance from the Magic's 65% team shooting ensured the team a Game 3 win and the first Finals victory in franchise history. Although they trailed the Magic as much as 12 at halftime, the Lakers won Game 4 in overtime on the back of [[Trevor Ariza]]'s 13 points in the second half and Fisher's pair of three-point clutch shots. Dominant offensive play coupled with a spectacular defense by both starters and reserves from the second quarter until the buzzer helped the Lakers to win Game 5 and secure the series. Bryant was named [[Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] of the Finals.\n\nRodd Houston narrated the Lakers' 2009 season through the Lakers 2009 championship home video on [[NBA Entertainment]]. As with previous championship videos, two versions exist: the DVD version recaps the entire 2009 Lakers' season, from the regular season and playoffs to the finals; the TV version recaps only the Lakers' playoff run.\n\nThis series was nicknamed the \"'''Disney Series'''\" for its connections to [[The Walt Disney Company]]. Disney owns both [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]], and Finals broadcaster [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]; [[Walt Disney World]] is located {{convert|20|mi}} from Orlando in nearby [[Lake Buena Vista, Florida|Lake Buena Vista]], and [[Disneyland]] is located {{convert|30|mi}} from Los Angeles in nearby [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]].\n\n==Series summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Game !! Date !! Away Team !! Result !! Home Team\n|-\n| Game 1 || Thursday, June 4 || Orlando Magic || 75\u2013100 (0\u20131) || '''Los Angeles Lakers''' \n|-\n| Game 2 || Sunday, June 7 || Orlando Magic || 96\u2013101 (0\u20132) || '''Los Angeles Lakers''' \n|-\n| Game 3 || Tuesday, June 9 || Los Angeles Lakers  || 104\u2013108 (2\u20131) || '''Orlando Magic'''\n|-\n| Game 4 || Thursday, June 11 || '''Los Angeles Lakers'''  || 99\u201391 (3\u20131) || Orlando Magic\n|-\n| Game 5 || Sunday, June 14 || '''Los Angeles Lakers'''  || 99\u201386 (4\u20131) || Orlando Magic\n|-\n|}\n\n==Background==\nThe two team captains (the Lakers' [[Kobe Bryant]] and the Magic's [[Dwight Howard]]) were teammates and starters on the [[USA men's national basketball team|United States men's national team]] the previous summer, winning a [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics|gold medal]] at the [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men|2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing]]. Each player defeated another fellow Olympic starter in his respective conference final series: Bryant defeated [[Carmelo Anthony]]'s [[Denver Nuggets]] and Howard advanced past [[LeBron James|LeBron James']] [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].\n\n===2009 NBA Playoffs===\n{{Main|2009 NBA Playoffs}}\n{|width=100% border=0 class=wikitable\n|- valign=top\n!colspan=2 width=45%|[[Los Angeles Lakers]] ([[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] champion) !!colspan=2 width=45%|[[Orlando Magic]] ([[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] champion)\n|-\n|align=right|{{2008\u201309 NBA West standings|team=LAL}}1st seed in the West, 2nd best league record\n!colspan=2|[[2008\u201309 NBA season|Regular season]]\n|align=left|{{2008\u201309 NBA East standings|team=ORL}}3rd seed in the East, 4th best league record\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the (8) [[Utah Jazz]], 4\u20131\n!colspan=2|First Round\n|align=left|Defeated the (6) [[Philadelphia 76ers]], 4\u20132\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the (5) [[Houston Rockets]], 4\u20133\n!colspan=2|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|Defeated the (2) [[Boston Celtics]], 4\u20133\n|-\n|align=right|Defeated the (2) [[Denver Nuggets]], 4\u20132\n!colspan=2|Conference Finals\n|align=left|Defeated the (1) [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], 4\u20132\n|}\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers===\n{{Main|2008\u201309 Los Angeles Lakers season}}\nThe [[Los Angeles Lakers|Lakers]] were the favorite to emerge from the Western Conference, but their road to the Finals was a tough one. They played three physical series against the [[Utah Jazz]], [[Houston Rockets]], and [[Denver Nuggets]], winning in 5, 7, and 6 games, respectively. Going into the Finals, the Lakers finished off the Nuggets in the Western Conference Finals with two good performances in games 5 and 6, making analysts pick them as the favorites in the Finals. It marked a record-extending sixth Finals appearance of the decade and a record-extending 30th Finals appearance overall, the most for any NBA team.\n\n===Orlando Magic===\n{{Main|2008\u201309 Orlando Magic season}}\nThe [[Orlando Magic|Magic]] were overlooked by many to even reach the Eastern Conference Finals, as they played in the shadows of the #1-seeded [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], led by regular-season [[NBA MVP|MVP]] [[LeBron James]], and defending champion #2-seed [[Boston Celtics]]. However, after dispatching the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in six games, the Magic stunned the Celtics by winning [[List of NBA game sevens|Game 7]] in [[Boston]]. The Celtics were previously 32\u20130 when leading a series 3\u20132, and 17\u20133 previously in Game 7s at home. Orlando assistant coach [[Patrick Ewing]] had publicly \"guaranteed\" that Orlando would win game 7.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/recap;_ylt=AlT7qdkLBThF5x98WEzpSs.8vLYF?gid=2009051702&prov=ap|title=Magic Moment: Orlando beats Boston to advance|first=Jimmy|last=Golen|date=May 18, 2009|agency=Associated Press|work=Yahoo.com|quote=Magic assistant coach Patrick Ewing had guaranteed a victory. But Celtics coach [[Doc Rivers]], who had been Ewing\u2019s teammate with the New York Knicks, laughed it off.| accessdate= 29 July 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\nIn the next round, Orlando was given little chance by many to defeat the top-seeded Cleveland Cavaliers, but a combination of three-point shooting and the inside presence of [[Dwight Howard]] created a matchup nightmare for Cleveland on defense, and Orlando ultimately won in six games. In Game 6, Howard's stellar performance with 40 points and 14 rebounds helped the franchise earn its second Finals appearance (they were swept by the [[Houston Rockets]] in the {{nbafy|1995}} Finals during [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Penny Hardaway]] era).\n\n===Series preview===\nAlthough the Magic won both regular-season matchups with the Lakers, Los Angeles was able to take 4 out of 5 games in this series. Both regular-season games and three of the NBA Finals games were close contests, decided by six points or fewer or in overtime. The Lakers won Game 2 on June 7 101\u201396 in overtime. Then they won Game 4 on June 11 in overtime as well.\n\n[[Tyronn Lue]], a backup point guard with Orlando, appeared with the Lakers during their initial championship run in the early 2000s and faced his former team in the finals. Lue and another backup point guard, [[Anthony Johnson (basketball)|Anthony Johnson]] were the only players on Orlando's roster with NBA finals experience. However, neither saw playing time during the series, as Lue was inactive with an injury and Johnson lost his minutes to teammate [[Jameer Nelson]], who returned from a shoulder injury in time for the Finals, where he led the Magic to sweep the Lakers in regular season. [[Trevor Ariza]], the Lakers starting small forward, faced the team who traded him to the Lakers in 2007.\n\n====Regular-season series====\nThe [[Orlando Magic]] won both games in the regular-season series:\n{{basketballbox\n| bg=#fff\n| date = December 20, 2008\n| report = {{NBA Recap|2008|1220|id=LALORL}}\n| team1 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score1=103 \n| team2 = '''[[Orlando Magic]] |score2=106'''\n| place = [[Amway Arena]], [[Orlando, Florida]]\n}}\n{{basketballbox\n| date = January 16, 2009\n| report = {{NBA Recap|2009|0116|id=ORLLAL}}\n| team1 = '''[[Orlando Magic]] |score1=109'''\n| team2 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score2=103\n| place = [[Staples Center]], [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]\n}}\n\n==Game summaries==\n:''All times are in [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Daylight Time]] ([[UTC\u22124]]).''\n\n===Game 1===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 4 |time=9:00 p.m. |place=[[Staples Center]], [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] |TV=[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1=[[Orlando Magic]] |score1=75\n|team2='''[[Los Angeles Lakers]]''' |score2='''100'''\n|Q1='''24'''\u201322 |Q2=19\u2013'''31''' |Q3=15\u2013'''29''' |Q4=17\u2013'''18'''\n|points1=[[Micka\u00ebl Pi\u00e9trus]] 14 |points2=[[Kobe Bryant]] 40\n|rebounds1=[[Dwight Howard]] 15 |rebounds2=[[Lamar Odom]] 14\n|assist1=[[Jameer Nelson]] 4 |assist2=[[Kobe Bryant]] 8\n|report={{NBA Recap|2009|0604|id=ORLLAL}}<br />{{YouTube|ImYGQWmK9ho|Video highlights}}\n|attendance=18,997\n|referee = \n* No. 43 [[Dan Crawford (basketball referee)|Dan Crawford]]\n* No. 14 [[Joe DeRosa (referee)|Joe DeRosa]]\n* No. 41 [[Ken Mauer]]\n|series=L.A. Lakers leads series, 1\u20130\n}}\nAfter an evenly battled first quarter, the Magic took the lead thanks to field goals and assists from point guard [[Jameer Nelson]], who was playing his first game since injuring his shoulder during the regular season in February. Down 33\u201328 with 8:38 left in the 2nd quarter, the Lakers went on a 10\u20130 run and never looked back. The Lakers ended the 3rd quarter on a 25\u201310 run, led by the fierce play from [[Kobe Bryant]], who finished with 40 points, 8 rebounds, and 8 assists, joining the likes of [[Shaquille O'Neal]], [[Michael Jordan]], and [[Jerry West]] to put up those numbers in a single NBA Finals game. The 25-point margin of victory was the 6th-largest in NBA Finals Game 1 history.\n\nDue to stellar defense by the Lakers, Dwight Howard was a dismal 1\u20136 from the field, his fewest made field goals in his playoff career, and finished with 12 points, 10 of which came from free throws. The Magic shot only 29.9% (23\u201377) from the field, the second lowest percentage in the NBA Finals.\n\n===Game 2===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 7 |time=8:00 p.m. |place=[[Staples Center]], [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] |TV=[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1=[[Orlando Magic]] |score1=96\n|team2='''[[Los Angeles Lakers]]''' |score2='''101'''\n|Q1=15\u201315 |Q2=20\u2013'''25''' |Q3='''30'''\u201323 |Q4=23\u2013'''25''' |OT=8\u2013'''13'''\n|points1=[[Rashard Lewis]] 34 |points2=[[Kobe Bryant]] 29\n|rebounds1=[[Dwight Howard]] 16 |rebounds2=[[Pau Gasol]] 10\n|assist1=[[Rashard Lewis]] 7 |assist2=[[Kobe Bryant]] 8\n|report={{NBA Recap|2009|0607|id=ORLLAL}}<br />{{YouTube|saSgjfA5x9Q|Video highlights}}\n|attendance=18,997\n|referee = \n* No. 29 [[Steve Javie]]\n* No. 13 [[Monty McCutchen]]\n* No. 49 Tom Washington\n|series=L.A. Lakers leads series, 2\u20130\n}}\n\nBoth teams got off to a slow start and were tied at 15 after the first quarter, setting a record-low for combined score (30) in the first quarter of an NBA Finals game. The Lakers picked up the pace in the 2nd quarter, but [[Rashard Lewis]] kept the Magic in the game, scoring 18 of the team's 20 points in the quarter, including the final 16, on his way to a playoff career-high and Finals franchise-high 34 points for the game. The Magic outscored the Lakers in the 3rd quarter to take a 2-point lead in the 4th.\n\nWith the game tied at 84, Rashard Lewis hit a jumper with 1:32 remaining to give the Magic a 2-point lead. Kobe Bryant responded with a jumper of his own to tie the game. With 47 seconds left, [[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]] hit a jumper that was originally called a 3-pointer. However, replay showed that his foot was on the line, giving the Magic a 2-point lead. With 33 seconds remaining, [[Dwight Howard]] was able to deflect, but not steal, a [[Derek Fisher]] pass, and [[Pau Gasol]] was able to again tie the game at 88 with a layup.\n\nOn the ensuing Magic possession, the Lakers played great defense and forced [[Courtney Lee]] to miss an awkward layup shot with 10.5 seconds left. With a chance to take a 2\u20130 series lead, Kobe Bryant was blocked on a jumper by T\u00fcrko\u011flu, who gained control of the ball and called time-out with 0.6 seconds left. After another timeout, T\u00fcrko\u011flu threw a half-court lob to Courtney Lee, who had come free after a screen on his defender. However, Lee was traveling too fast and launched his layup from almost behind the backboard, causing it to miss.\n\nWith the Lakers up 1 in overtime with 1:55 left, Derek Fisher stole a [[J. J. Redick]] pass and was fouled on the ensuing fastbreak, making both free throws. After the Magic were unable to convert, Kobe Bryant made a pivotal assist to Pau Gasol for a layup-and-one, giving the Lakers a 6-point lead and the eventual victory.\n\n===Game 3===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 9 |time=9:00 p.m. |place=[[Amway Arena]], [[Orlando, Florida]] |TV=[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1=[[Los Angeles Lakers]] |score1=104\n|team2='''[[Orlando Magic]]''' |score2='''108'''\n|Q1='''31'''\u201327|Q2=23\u2013'''32''' |Q3=21\u2013'''22''' |Q4='''29'''\u201327\n|points1=[[Kobe Bryant]] 31 |points2=[[Dwight Howard|Howard]], [[Rashard Lewis|Lewis]] 21 each\n|rebounds1=[[Trevor Ariza]] 7 |rebounds2=[[Dwight Howard]] 14\n|assist1=[[Kobe Bryant]] 8 |assist2=[[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]] 7\n|report={{NBA Recap|2009|0609|id=LALORL}}<br />{{YouTube|L9TS1M7LL6k|Video highlights}}\n|attendance=17,461\n|referee = \n* No. 17 [[Joe Crawford (basketball, born 1951)|Joe Crawford]]\n* No. 9 Derrick Stafford\n* No. 18 [[Mark Wunderlich]]\n|series=L.A. Lakers leads series, 2\u20131\n}}\n\nThe Magic came out in Game 3 with fire. The Magic shot a field goal percentage of 63% for the game, a Finals record. This also included a 75% first quarter, also a Finals record. However, despite the incredible shooting percentage, the Lakers managed to stay close for much of the game. The game was only sealed for the Magic on a Mikael Pietrus steal from Kobe Bryant in the waning minute of the 4th quarter.\n\nThis win marked the first Finals win in Magic franchise history, losing their first 6 Finals games (being swept in their first appearance and losing Games 1 and 2)\n\n===Game 4===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 11 |time=9:00 p.m. |place=[[Amway Arena]], [[Orlando, Florida]] |TV=[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1='''[[Los Angeles Lakers]]''' |score1='''99''' \n|team2=[[Orlando Magic]] |score2=91\n|Q1=20\u2013'''24''' |Q2=17\u2013'''25''' |Q3='''30'''\u201314 |Q4=20\u2013'''24''' |OT='''12'''\u20134\n|points1=[[Kobe Bryant]] 32 |points2=[[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]] 25\n|rebounds1=[[Pau Gasol]] 10 |rebounds2=[[Dwight Howard]] 21\n|assist1=[[Kobe Bryant]] 8 |assist2=[[Rashard Lewis]] 4\n|report={{NBA Recap|2009|0611|id=LALORL}}<br />{{YouTube|o4xg3TyVV_Y|Video highlights}}\n|attendance=17,461\n|referee = \n* No. 24 Mike Callahan\n* No. 48 [[Scott Foster (referee)|Scott Foster]]\n* No. 15 [[Bennett Salvatore]]\n|series=L.A. Lakers leads series, 3\u20131\n}}\n\nComing off their franchise's first NBA Finals game victory, the Magic quickly took the lead in the first quarter. However, [[Kobe Bryant]] kept the Lakers in the game, scoring 13 of the team's 20 first-quarter points. [[Dwight Howard]] played a great first quarter, with 11 rebounds and 4 blocks in the opening frame. In addition, he drew many fouls, putting [[Andrew Bynum]], [[Pau Gasol]], and [[Lamar Odom]] in foul trouble and forcing Lakers coach [[Phil Jackson]] to use [[Josh Powell]] and [[D. J. Mbenga]] early in the game. The Magic were able to increase the lead to 12 at halftime.\n\nThe Lakers came out of the locker room aggressive and outscored the Magic 30\u201314 in the 3rd quarter, led by [[Trevor Ariza]], who scored 13 points in the quarter, including two 3-pointers. Down by 6 in the opening minutes of the 4th quarter, the Magic were able to come back to take a 76\u201375 lead halfway through the quarter, but unable to increase the lead due to poor free-throw shooting, specifically from [[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]] and [[Dwight Howard]].\n\nWith 3 minutes left in the 4th quarter and the game tied at 79, Howard converted a 3-point play to give the Magic an 82\u201379 lead. On the next Laker possession, the Magic played good defense, but Trevor Ariza was able to hit a 3-pointer as the shot clock expired to tie the game at 82. After Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu hit a stepback 3-point shot, Howard blocked Gasol's jumper, giving him a single-game NBA Finals record with 9 blocked shots. On the bench to witness it was a previous record holder, his assistant coach [[Patrick Ewing]], who had 8 in Game 5 of the [[1994 NBA Finals]] while with the [[New York Knicks]]. T\u00fcrko\u011flu made another jumper with 1:34 remaining to give the Magic a 5-point lead.\n\nDown 87\u201382 with 31 seconds left, [[Kobe Bryant]] spun through the lane and passed to Gasol for a dunk to cut the lead to 3. On the next Magic possession, Howard was fouled by Bryant with 11 seconds remaining. Needing just one free-throw to make the game a 2-possession affair, Howard missed both shots.\n\nOut of the timeout, the Lakers elected to take the ball out at three-quarters court instead of half-court in order to space out the floor. The Magic double-teamed Bryant in the backcourt, allowing him to pass the ball up to Ariza, who in turned passed it to [[Derek Fisher]] on the right wing. Having missed his first five 3-point shots of the game, Fisher spotted up and hit a pivotal three-pointer over Jameer Nelson to tie the game at 87 with 4.6 seconds left. On the final possession of regulation, [[Micka\u00ebl Pi\u00e9trus]] missed a 20-footer.\n\nThe overtime session began with a 3-pointer by [[Rashard Lewis]] and two contested jumpers by [[Kobe Bryant]] to give the Lakers a 91\u201390 lead. With 1:27 left in OT, Howard split a pair of free throws to tie the game at 91. On the next possession, the Lakers would miss a layup and a jumper, but regained possession on an offensive rebound by Ariza and a loose-ball foul on [[Jameer Nelson]]. With 31 seconds left, Kobe Bryant passed out of a double-team with the controversy of no called on Jameer Nelson after being knocked out by Kobe Bryant. Before, Fisher then hit a 3-pointer to give the Lakers a 94\u201391 lead.\n\nOut of a timeout, T\u00fcrko\u011flu rushed a 3-point shot and missed. Rashard Lewis backtapped the rebound to center-court, but the ball went to Pau Gasol, who ran in unimpeded for a dunk, giving the Lakers the lead for good. In the next possession, the Magic missed another shot, bouncing the ball to Fisher, who passed it to Ariza, then to Gasol for a dunk, but Pietrus slammed both arms on his back, resulting in Gasol getting a technical foul and Pietrus a flagrant 1 foul.\n\nAfter coming so close, the Magic lost a chance to tie the series, a fact not lost upon the arena staff in Orlando. Upon the game's finish, [[Oasis (band)|Oasis's]] \"[[Don't Look Back in Anger]]\" was played throughout Amway Arena.\n\n===Game 5===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=June 14 |time=8:00 p.m. |place=[[Amway Center]], [[Orlando, Florida]] |TV=[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]\n|team1='''[[Los Angeles Lakers]]''' |score1='''99'''\n|team2=[[Orlando Magic]] |score2= 86\n|report={{NBA Recap|2009|0614|id=LALORL}}<br />{{YouTube|u_qNvMeVsZc|Video highlights}}\n|Q1=26\u2013'''28''' |Q2='''30'''\u201318 |Q3='''20'''\u201315 |Q4=23\u2013'''25'''\n|points1=[[Kobe Bryant]] 30 |points2=[[Rashard Lewis]] 18\n|rebounds1=[[Pau Gasol]] 15 |rebounds2=[[Dwight Howard|Howard]], [[Rashard Lewis|Lewis]] 10 each\n|assist1=[[Kobe Bryant]] 5 |assist2=[[Rashard Lewis|Lewis]], [[Jameer Nelson|Nelson]] 4 each\n|attendance=17,461\n|referee= \n* No. 43 [[Dan Crawford (basketball referee)|Dan Crawford]]\n* No. 14 [[Joe DeRosa (referee)|Joe DeRosa]]\n* No. 41 [[Ken Mauer]]\n|series=L.A. Lakers wins series 4\u20131\n}}\n\nThe Magic, facing the prospect of the Lakers winning a championship on their home floor, came out with a good start, leading by as much as 9 in the first quarter. In the opening frame, all 5 starters scored and assisted on at least one field goal, but the Lakers pulled to within 2 at the quarter break. Down 40\u201336 with 7:11 in the 2nd quarter, the Lakers went on a 16\u20130 run, fueled by two 3-pointers and solid defensive play from [[Trevor Ariza]]. The Lakers led by as much as 12 in the 2nd quarter and the score was 56\u201346 at halftime.\n\nComing out of the half, Orlando cut the lead to 5 with 7:45 remaining in the 3rd on a 3-pointer by [[Rafer Alston]]. [[Lamar Odom]] answered with back-to-back 3-pointers to restore the Laker lead to double digits. Leading by as much as 18 in the half, Los Angeles led by 15 going into the 4th quarter. In the final quarter, Orlando attempted a run but managed to cut the lead down to only 12; at the buzzer, the Lakers celebrated their 15th title.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Withers|title=Bryant, Lakers reign once more|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20090614/LALORL/recap.html|publisher=[[National Basketball Association]]|date=2009-06-14|accessdate=2009-06-15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618135606/http://www.nba.com/games/20090614/LALORL/recap.html|archivedate=18 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the game, NBA Commissioner [[David Stern]] presented the Lakers with the [[Larry O'Brien Championship Trophy]] and presented [[Kobe Bryant]] with the [[Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award|Bill Russell NBA Finals MVP Trophy]] during a presentation on center-court at [[Amway Arena]]. Bryant averaged 32.4 points, 5.6 rebounds and 7.4 assists per game during the series.\n\n==Statistics==\n{{listen\n|filename=Welcoming The Lakers To The White House (1-25-10) Barack Obama.ogv\n|title=January 25, 2010 White House Visit\n|description=On January 25, 2010, [[Barack Obama]] hosted the [[2008\u201309 Los Angeles Lakers season|2008\u201309 Los Angeles Lakers]] at the [[White House]] following their victory in the 2009 NBA Finals to end the [[2008\u201309 NBA season]].\n|filetype=[[Ogv]]}}\nThe series was the third straight championship that the Lakers clinched on the road (after [[2001 NBA Finals|2001]] and [[2002 NBA Finals|2002]]); the last time the Lakers clinched the championship at home was in [[2000 NBA Finals|2000]]. With their team's win, [[Pau Gasol]] became the first [[Spain|Spaniard]], and [[D. J. Mbenga]] the first [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congolese]] player, to win an NBA championship. [[Bill Walton|Bill]] and [[Luke Walton]] became the third father and son pair to each win a championship as a player; the other father\u2013son combinations are [[Matt Guokas, Sr.]] ([[1947 NBA Finals|1947]]) with [[Matt Guokas|Matt Jr.]] ([[1967 NBA Finals|1967]]) and [[Rick Barry]] ([[1975 NBA Finals|1975]]) with son [[Brent Barry|Brent]] ([[2005 NBA Finals|2005]] and [[2007 NBA Finals|2007]]). [[Kobe Bryant]] averaged 32.4 points and 7.4 assists in this series, which was the best combination of those categories since [[Jerry West]] averaged 37.9 points and 7.4 assists ([[1969 NBA Finals|1969]]).\n\nFor the Magic, Game 3 marked their first Finals game victory; the franchise lost their first six Finals games after being swept in their first Finals appearance in [[1995 NBA Finals|1995]]. In Game 3, the Magic also set the Finals record for the best [[Field goal (basketball)|field goal]] percentage with 63 percent, and the Finals record for the best field goal percentage in the first half with 75 percent.\n\nThis was the first NBA Finals series since [[1984 NBA Finals|1984]] to have two games go into overtime (Games 2 and 4); both were won by the Lakers. [[Dwight Howard]] set an NBA Finals single-game record with 9 blocked shots in Game 4. The previous record holders, all of whom had blocked eight shots in a Finals game,<ref>http://www.nba.com/history/records/finals_game_blockedshots.html</ref> were: [[Bill Walton]] of the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] in Game 6 of the [[1977 NBA Finals]]; [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] of the [[Houston Rockets]] in Game 5 of the [[1986 NBA Finals]]; Howard's assistant coach [[Patrick Ewing]] of the [[New York Knicks]] in Game 5 of the [[1994 NBA Finals]]; [[Shaquille O'Neal]] of the Los Angeles Lakers in Game 2 of the [[2001 NBA Finals]]; and [[Tim Duncan]] of the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in Game 6 of the [[2003 NBA Finals]].\n\nThis is the seventh time in NBA Finals history that a team that lost the championship the previous season has won the Finals the very next year. It is the second time in Lakers history, after the [[1984 NBA Finals|1984]] and [[1985 NBA Finals|1985]] teams.\n\nThis is also the first odd season since 2001 that the [[San Antonio Spurs]] did not win the NBA Finals; they won in [[2003 NBA Finals|2003]], [[2005 NBA Finals|2005]] and [[2007 NBA Finals|2007]].\n\nThis was the last Finals in which a trophy silhouette was painted in mid-court. The tradition began in [[2005 NBA Finals|2005]] and ended for the [[2010 NBA Finals|2010]] series. This was also the last NBA Finals to be played at [[Amway Arena]]; the Magic moved to the [[Amway Center]] for the [[2010-11 NBA season|2010-11 season]].\n \n{|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=3|Category !!rowspan=2 colspan=2|High !!colspan=4|Average\n|-\n! colspan=2|[[Los Angeles Lakers]] !! colspan=2|[[Orlando Magic]]\n|-\n!Player !! Total !! Player !! Avg. !! Player !! Avg.\n|-\n| [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kobe Bryant]] || 40\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kobe Bryant]] || 32.4 || {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]] || 18.0\n|-\n| [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dwight Howard]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Dwight Howard]] || 21 <small>(OT)</small><br>15\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Pau Gasol]] || 9.2 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dwight Howard]] || 15.2\n|-\n| [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kobe Bryant]] || 8\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kobe Bryant]] || 7.4 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Rashard Lewis]] || 4.0\n|-\n| [[Steal (basketball)|Steals]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dwight Howard]]<br>{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Micka\u00ebl Pi\u00e9trus]] || 4 <small>(OT)</small><br>3\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Trevor Ariza]] || 1.8 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dwight Howard]] || 1.6\n|-\n| [[Block (basketball)|Blocks]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dwight Howard]]<br>{{flagicon|POL}} [[Marcin Gortat]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kobe Bryant]]<br>{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Pau Gasol]] || 9 <small>(OT)</small><br>4<br>4<br>4\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Pau Gasol]] || 1.8 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dwight Howard]] || 4.0\n|}\n\n==2009 NBA Finals rosters==\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers===\n<!-- This is an intentionally substituted copy of [[Template:Los Angeles Lakers roster]] kept as a \"snapshot\" for this championship round -->\n{{NBA roster header|team=Los Angeles Lakers|season=2008\u201309}}\n<!-- list of players -->\n{{player2 | num = 3 |nat = USA | first = Trevor | last = Ariza | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 8 | lbs = 210 | From = Miami, Florida |college = UCLA }}\n{{player2 | num = 12 | nat = USA | first = Shannon | last = Brown| pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 4 | lbs = 211 | college = Michigan State }}\n{{player2 | num = 24 | nat = USA | nat2 = ITA | first = Kobe | last = Bryant | pos = G/F | ft = 6 | in = 6 | lbs = 205 | college = [[Lower Merion High School|Lower Merion HS (PA)]] | note = C }}\n{{player2 | num = 17 | nat = USA | first = Andrew | last = Bynum | pos = C | ft = 7 | in = 0 | lbs = 285 | college = [[St. Joseph High School (Metuchen, New Jersey)|St. Joseph HS (NJ)]] }}\n{{player2 | num = 5 | nat = USA | first = Jordan | last = Farmar | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 2 | lbs = 180 | college = UCLA| }}\n{{player2 | num = 2 | nat = USA | first = Derek | last = Fisher | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 1 | lbs = 205 | college = UALR }}\n{{player2 | num = 16 | nat = ESP| first = Pau | last = Gasol | pos = F/C | ft = 7 | in = 0 | lbs = 260 | from = Spain }}\n{{player2 | num = 28| nat = BEL| link = D. J. Mbenga | alt= Ilunga-Mbenga, Didier | pos = C | ft = 7 | in = 0 | lbs = 255 | from = Belgium }}\n{{player2 | num = 6 | nat = USA | first = Adam | last = Morrison | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 8 | lbs = 205 | college = Gonzaga }}\n{{player2 | num = 7 | nat = USA | first = Lamar | last = Odom | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 10 | lbs = 230 | college = Rhode Island }}\n{{player2 | num = 21 | nat = USA | first = Josh | last = Powell | pos = F/C | ft = 6 | in = 9 | lbs = 225 | college = North Carolina State }}\n{{player2 | num = 18 | nat = SLO | first = Sasha | last = Vuja\u010di\u0107 | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 7 | lbs = 195 | from = Slovenia }}\n{{player2 | num = 4 | nat = USA | first = Luke | last = Walton | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 8 | lbs = 232 | college = Arizona }}\n{{player2 | num = 9 | nat = CHN | first = Sun | last = Yue |dab=basketball| pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 7 | lbs = 205 | from = China}}\n<!-- end list of players -->\n{{NBA roster footer\n| head_coach = \n* {{player||USA|[[Phil Jackson]]}} ({{college|North Dakota}})\n| asst_coach = \n*{{player||USA|[[Frank Hamblen]]}} ({{college|Syracuse}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Kurt Rambis]]}} ({{college|Santa Clara}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Brian Shaw]]}} ({{college|UC-Santa Barbara}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]]}} ({{college|UCLA}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Craig Hodges]]}} ({{college|Long Beach State}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Jim Cleamons]]}} ({{college|Ohio State}})\n| roster_url = http://www.nba.com/lakers/roster/\n| transaction_url = http://www.hoopshype.com/general_managers/mitch_kupchak.htm\n| accessdate = 2009-02-18\n}}\n\n===Orlando Magic===\n<!-- This is an intentionally substituted copy of [[Template:Orlando Magic roster]] kept as a \"snapshot\" for this championship round -->\n{{NBA roster header|team=Orlando Magic|season=2008\u201309}}\n<!-- list of players -->\n{{player2 | num = 1 | first = Rafer | last = Alston | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 2 | lbs = 175 | college = Fresno State | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 4 | first = Tony | last = Battie | pos = F/C | ft = 6 | in = 11 | lbs = 240 | college = Texas Tech | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 31 | first = Adonal | last = Foyle | pos = C | ft = 6 | in = 10 | lbs = 270 | college = Colgate | nat = VIN}}\n{{player2 | num = 13 | first = Marcin | last = Gortat | pos = C | ft = 6 | in = 11 | lbs = 240 | from = Poland | nat = POL}}\n{{player2 | num = 12 | first = Dwight | last = Howard | pos = C | ft = 6 | in = 11 | lbs = 265 | school = Southwest Atlanta Christian Academy | nat = USA | note = C}}\n{{player2 | num = 8 | first = Anthony | last = Johnson | dab = basketball | pos = PG | ft = 6 | in = 3 | lbs = 195 | college = C of C | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 11 | first = Courtney | last = Lee | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 5 | lbs = 200 | school = Western Kentucky | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 9 | first = Rashard | last = Lewis | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 10 | lbs = 230 | school = Alief Elsik High School | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 10 | first = Tyronn | last = Lue | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 0 | lbs = 175 | school = Nebraska | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 14 | first = Jameer | last = Nelson | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 0 | lbs = 190 | college = St. Joseph's | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 20 | first = Micka\u00ebl | last = Pi\u00e9trus | pos = G/F | ft = 6 | in = 6 | lbs = 215 | from = France | France | nat = FRA}}\n{{player2 | num = 7 | first = J. J. | last = Redick | pos = G | ft = 6 | in = 4 | lbs = 190 | college = Duke | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 32 | first = Jeremy | last = Richardson | pos = G/F | ft = 6 | in = 7 | lbs = 195 | college = Delta State | nat = USA}}\n{{player2 | num = 15 | first = Hedo | last = T\u00fcrko\u011flu | pos = F | ft = 6 | in = 10 | lbs = 220 | from = Turkey | nat = TUR}}\n<!-- end list of players -->\n{{NBA roster footer\n| head_coach = \n*{{player||USA|[[Stan Van Gundy]]}} ({{college|SUNY-Brockport}})\n| asst_coach =\n*{{player||USA|[[Brendan Malone]]}} ({{college|Iona}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Steve Clifford]]}} ({{college|Maine}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Patrick Ewing]]}} ({{college|Georgetown}})\n*{{player||USA|[[Bob Beyer]]}} ({{college|Alfred}})\n| roster_url = http://www.nba.com/magic/roster/\n| transaction_url = http://www.hoopshype.com/general_managers/otis_smith.htm\n| accessdate = 2009-03-23\n}}\n\n==Player statistics==\n{{NBA roster statistics legend}}\n\n;Los Angeles Lakers\n{{NBA roster statistics start|team=Los Angeles Lakers}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Trevor|Ariza}} || 5 || 5 || 37.6 || .357 || .417 || .500 || 6.0 || 1.6 || '''1.8''' || 0.2 || 11.0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Shannon|Brown}} || 3 || 0 || 5.2 || .000 || .000 || .000 || 0.3 || 0.0 || 0.0 || 0.0 || 0.0\n|-! style=\"background:#FDE910;\"\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Kobe|Bryant}} || 5 || 5 || '''43.8''' || .430 || .360 || .841 || 5.6 || '''7.4''' || 1.4 || 1.4 || '''32.4'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Andrew|Bynum}} || 5 || 5 || 18.9 || .364 || .000 || .667 || 4.2 || 0.6 || 0.4 || 0.6 || 6.0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Jordan|Farmar}} || 5 || 0 || 11.5 || .368 || .125 || '''1.000''' || 1.2 || 0.4 || 0.4 || 0.0 || 3.4\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Derek|Fisher}} || 5 || 5 || 35.9 || .500 || .438 || '''1.000''' || 3.0 || 1.8 || 1.2 || 0.0 || 11.0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Pau|Gasol}} || 5 || 5 || 42.5 || .600 || .000 || .778 || '''9.2''' || 2.2 || 0.8 || '''1.8''' || 18.6\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|D. J.|Mbenga}} || 3 || 0 || 2.0 || .000 || .000 || .000 || 0.3 || 0.0 || 0.0 || 0.3 || 0.0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Lamar|Odom}} || 5 || 0 || 33.8 || .542 || .500 || .688 || 7.8 || 0.8 || 1.0 || 1.0 || 13.4\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Josh|Powell}} || 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .500 || '''1.000''' || .000 || 2.0 || 0.5 || 0.0 || 0.0 || 2.5\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | {{sortname|Sasha|Vuja\u010di\u0107}} || 5 || 0 || 4.4 || .000 || .000 || 